<HEAD>26 Sinhalese Militants Surrender</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Wednesday declared a week-long cease-fire with Sinhalese and Tamil rebels, and an official said 26 Sinhalese militants surrendered under President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s peace plan. The militants, belonging to the <ORGANIZATION> Marxist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, gave themselves up at temples and government offices Wednesday, said the military official, who can not be identified under briefing rules. He did not give details. <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>, seeking to end six years of ethnic violence that has claimed 12,500 lives, announced a general amnesty and unilateral cease-fire to Sinhalese and Tamil rebels. The offer was part of a peace package that included seats in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and jobs for the militants. The cease-fire began a day before Sinhalese and Tamils celebrate a common new year. The government also set up 228 centers at schools, temples and government offices across the country where the rebels could give themselves up. The front has not yet responded to the truce offer but the largest Tamil militant group, campaigning to set up an independent state in Northern and Northeastern Provinces, rejected it outright Tuesday. However, `` the militants have a week to surrender and it is too early to make a decision about the response to the surrender call,'' the military official said. No militants surrendered in the capital. The chief priest of <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> temples in <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> said `` nobody turned up'' at the shrines where reception centers were set up for receiving the rebels. An official at a reception center in <LOCATION> Weligama </LOCATION>, 85 miles south of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, said on the telephone: `` We have a whole lot of armed police here but nobody to surrender.'' The south is the Sinhalese heartland where the Marxist rebels are most active. The extremists have been blamed for more than 2,500 political killings since January and most of the victims have been government officials and security men. The militants have been trying to topple the government since July 1987 when it signed a peace accord aimed at ending the Tamil separatist campaign. The left-wing extremists say the accord gave the minority Tamils too many concessions. They also say the presence of Indian troops, deployed to disarm the Tamil rebels and enforce the 1987 accord, compromises the country's independence. An Indian High Commission or embassy offical said <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> troops will continue to carry out operations against the Tamil rebels. But the troops will not hinder the `` process of surrendering,'' said the offical who can not be identified under briefing rules. The dominant Tamil rebel group, <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday: `` We will not agree to any cease-fire so long as the Indian army remains in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved in the conflict because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils to the rebel cause. Tamil militants launched a campaign in 1983 for an independent homeland, citing discrimination by the majority Sinhalese in employment and education. Tamils comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people. Most live in the Northern and <LOCATION> Northeastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Provinces </LOCATION>, where they want their homeland. Sinhalese make up 75 percent of the island's population and control the government and military
</TEXT>
