<HEAD>Government Says Troops Forced Guerrilla Retreat from Jalalabad</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with rebel government to move inside
Afghanistan. Picks up 3rd pvs, `Mohammad Karim...' ADDS 3 grafs on rebels
ask Security Council to stay clear.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Moslem guerrillas fired rockets and heavy artillery into the eastern city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, but Afghan troops returned fire and forced the guerrillas to retreat, a government spokesman said Wednesday. Also Wednesday, Iran-based guerrilla leaders were quoted as saying plans were under way for an offensive near <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, an <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> resistance leader, <PERSON> Gulbuddin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, said the resistance plans to shift its interim government this week from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> to the `` liberated'' <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> provinces of <LOCATION> Kunar </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Paktia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON>, foreign minister of the interim government set up in February by several guerrilla groups, told a news conference Wednesday that the entire Cabinet would move within the `` next two to three days,'' some ministries to <LOCATION> Asadabad </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Kunar </LOCATION>, and others to a site still be decided in <LOCATION> Paktia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hekmatyar </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> on an eight-nation tour to seek recognition for his government. <LOCATION> Malaysia </LOCATION> announced Tuesday if will formally recognize the interim government. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Karim </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalili </PERSON>, spokesman of the Iran-based guerrillas, said at a news conference in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> that `` forces in the city of <LOCATION> Meidan </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, and in <PERSON> Ghazi </PERSON> and areas to the north of the capital are preparing to start operations, and soon a new front will be opened near <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>,'' <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> radio reported. The guerrillas are split into the Iran-based Shiite coalition and the larger Sunni alliance based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The two have been at odds over the formation of a guerrilla government, in which the Shiite alliance is not represented. An unidentified official of the Shiite alliance was quoted by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> as saying that `` plans to attack <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> have been drawn up and efforts are under way to unite all mujahedeen groups for delivering the coup de grace.'' Pakistan-based guerrilla groups have been engaged in heavy fighting for <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> since March 6. <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabi </PERSON> <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said 19 civilians died and 15 were wounded in the latest rebel attack on <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>, 45 miles from the border with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. `` Government forces counterattacked and forced the opposition to halt their offensive and retreat,'' he said. <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> said there were no casualties among government soldiers. He said 271 guerrillas were killed and 201 were injured. The information could not be independently confirmed. The guerrillas, known as mujahedeen, or Islamic holy warriors, have been fighting nearly 11 years to topple <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s Marxist government. Capturing <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> is considered a key element in their strategy because it would give the guerrillas their first major urban foothold. <PERSON> Amani </PERSON> also said <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> checkpoints will be set up at six points along the Afghan-Pakistani border to check for aid <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> alleges is flowing to the guerrillas illegally from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> agreed Tuesday to allow the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> to set up permanent monitoring posts along the border. It denies the Afghan allegations. The checkpoints will be manned by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Good </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which monitored the withdrawal of Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Khalili </PERSON> said the Iran-based forces oppose the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> deployment. <PERSON> Rasul </PERSON> <PERSON> Sayyaf </PERSON>, prime minister of the rebels' provisional government, told <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> on Wednesday to stay clear of what he called a dying <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government's desperate tactic to draw the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> into a domestic war. In a letter, he asked the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> chief to pre-empt a <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> debate and if that was not possible, then to `` steer the debate on the right course _ <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> interference in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s ruling Marxists charged in an emergency session of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> was waging a `` full-fledged war'' against <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and intervening in the war by sending Pakistani army and milita to the battlefront. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> denied these charges, which have repeatedly been leveled by the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government.
