<HEAD>Swiss Housewife Appeals Fine For Airing Duvet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A housewife is appealing a $ 25 fine for airing her bedding after 10 a.m., saying the 30-year-old law that prohibits the practice is outdated. The woman has enlisted the help of a biochemist to back her claim that heavy pollution during morning rush hour makes it impossible to air her bedding `` legally,'' <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Suisse </ORGANIZATION> newspaper reported. Under 1955 public hygiene regulations in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, anyone living in an urban area who hangs duvets or carpets out of windows or over balconies in public view after 10 a.m. can be fined. The clause, which remained in obscurity, made headlines in Swiss newspapers Tuesday when the housewife, identified only as <PERSON> Claudine </PERSON>, appealed the fine she received after a zealous policeman spotted her offending duvet 30 minutes after the deadline.
