<HEAD>Record Price For A Koran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A miniature Koran by an unknown 10th century scribe was bought at auction for a record $ 297,000 for a European collection, <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s said. The auction house said the price paid Tuesday for the little book of 332 vellum pages, less than three inches tall and written in Eastern kufic script, was the highest ever paid for a Koran or part of one. `` Finely written small Korans are much prized and very saleable,'' said <PERSON> Caroline </PERSON> <PERSON> Blyth </PERSON>, the firm's head of Islamic manuscripts. `` This one was very old and had the status of coming from the estate of Crown Prince <PERSON> Muhammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirza </PERSON> <PERSON> Qajar </PERSON>, the sole pretender to the throne of the Qajar dynasty in <LOCATION> Persia </LOCATION> which ended in the 1920s,'' she said. The buyer was only identified as representing a European collection. <PERSON> Christie </PERSON>'s had put a top estimate on the Koran of $ 169,000. A single decorated leaf from a large Koran made the previous record of $ 268,000 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> in October.
