<HEAD>Bradley Seeks Fifth Term as Mayor, Low Voter Turnout Reported</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Bradley early leader, UPDATE
turnout; picks up 3rd graf, ``Although virtually ...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY FARAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> was the early leader in his campaign for a historic fifth term as mayor of the nation's second-largest city, capturing 54 percent of the absentee vote in a race characterized by low voter turnout <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, 71, the city's first black mayor, needed at least 50 percent of the vote to avoid a June 6 runoff. Forty-five minutes after the polls closed at 8 p.m., <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> was in the lead with 13,146 absentee ballots, or 54 percent, according to the City Clerk's Office. The next-closest contender was freshman City Councilman <PERSON> Nate </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON>, who received 5,014 absentee votes, or 20.66 percent. Former <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Supervisor and television commentator <PERSON> Baxter </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> had 4,800 votes, or 19.7 percent. Although virtually no observers believed the mayor could lose, one newspaper reported that a secret poll conducted by <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s campaign last week showed the mayor with just 53 percent of the vote <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> pollster <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Maullin </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Examiner </ORGANIZATION> that the polls conducted April 2 and 3 contained questions checking the impact of a city attorney's office ethics investigation of <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>. But, <PERSON> Maullin </PERSON> said, `` None of the results showed <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> not winning outright.'' City Clerk <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> had predicted a 25 percent to 30 percent turnout _ `` a historical low for a mayoral election.'' Voters faced morning low clouds and drizzle, and the turnout by 4 p.m. was only 11.6 percent of the city's 1.9 million registered voters. A poll taken recently by The <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> showed 78 percent of Hispanics, 70 percent of whites and 68 percent of blacks had a favorable impression of the Democratic mayor. That led <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> to be dubbed the `` Teflon mayor,'' because he is apparently not blamed for the city's mounting urban problems. The only currently elected official challenging <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, freshman City Councilman <PERSON> Nate </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON>, was considered his only serious opponent in the non-partisan race, but hardly a threat to the 16-year mayor. Other candidates included a former county supervisor, a socialist oil field worker and a singer-dancer who used to cavort in a green bikini across the street from City Hall every day. The winner of Tuesday's mayor's race will oversee <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> at least into the early 1990s, leading a city with a population that is swelling past 3 million people.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Pollsters and would-be opponents such as City Councilman <PERSON> Zev </PERSON> <PERSON> Yaroslavsky </PERSON> agree that <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s low-key image has kept him from being linked in voters' minds with <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' growing problems, including criminal gangs, illegal drug trade, traffic congestion and a failing sewage system. <PERSON> Yaroslavsky </PERSON> had widely been considered <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s leading challenger, but backed out of the race after apparently deciding that he could n't win. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s image even appeared untarnished by an ethics investigation by the city attorney's office, which learned that the mayor had performed consulting work with <ORGANIZATION> Far </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which did business with the city. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> returned the $ 18,000 in fees he was paid by the bank and called the charges politically motivated. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, the son of a <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> sharecropper and the grandson of slaves, was first elected mayor of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in 1973. A track star at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, he first entered public service as a <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> police lieutenant, and later was elected to the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> City Council. He was defeated in his first run at mayor in a bitter 1969 race against incumbent <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Yorty </PERSON> that critics said was tinged with racism, but came back to beat <PERSON> Yorty </PERSON> the next time around. At the end of his current term, <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> will become the first mayor in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> history to have served four full terms. He has run twice for governor, but was defeated in 1982 and 1986 by Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
