<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new sightseeing business has arrived on the scene in the nation's capital: guided tours conducted by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been taking his guests to see the sights, something predecessor <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> rarely did. For <LOCATION> Egyptian </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>, it was a trip by helicopter to nearby <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION> for a baseball game. There, the two presidents sat in a box and ate hot dogs and hamburgers and debated <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s high-and-outside season-opening pitch. For <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>, it was a trip past the <LOCATION> Tidal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Basin </LOCATION> for a glimpse of the city's famed cherry blossoms and then to the Air and Space Museum, one of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s most-visited attractions The two joined springtime tourists in the museum's wide-screened theater to watch the movie `` To Fly.'' Excited conversation rippled through the audience as people realized who was in their midst, and those who had cameras used them for snapshots. Next week, <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>'s King <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> will be in town. And it's anyone's guess where the president might take him `` <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is a city of 1,000 monuments,'' said White House press secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. `` We may end up visiting them all.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plans to take <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> to his vacation home in <LOCATION> Kennebunkport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, next month. And he threw open the doors of the presidential retreat at Camp David, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </P