<SECOND>PM-Drugs-Housing,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housing Officials Say Money Needed More than Policy Changes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Public housing officials say <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s anti-drug proposals may help in some housing projects but what they really need is more federal money to beef up security and help tenants find jobs. `` He's not suggesting anything that has not been thought of in the past _ they just have n't had the resources,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> and Redevelopment Officials. `` We've got a lot of hand-wringing going on but no help,'' said <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavanaugh </PERSON>, counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Large </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authorities </ORGANIZATION>. `` I have n't seen any money yet.'' The secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> proposed this week a series of steps for fighting drugs in federally supported housing projects in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. He said they `` are applicable to every public housing authority in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>'' and will be issued in `` action memos'' to all locally run public housing authorities. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s package includes only one direct <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> action: dropping government hearing procedures that may delay eviction of tenants who use or sell drugs, so long as the tenants receive due process in the courts. His other proposals were suggestions, including more police patrols, installing security fences around projects, establishing guarded entrances, renovating the projects and requiring photo identification cards for residents. He provided no cost estimate but said he would go to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to ask for more money if needed. District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> officials on Tuesday formally asked <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> to drop its requirement for hearings before evicting tenants for drug use or firearm violations. But some housing officials said the move might not be possible in some states, and that it might not speed up the eviction process very much in others. In <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, housing authority spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Toohey </PERSON> said, the hearing process works well and keeps most cases from ever going to court. `` We are not about to change our ... grievance procedures,'' he said. <PERSON> Cavanaugh </PERSON> said many of the nation's 3,000 public housing authorities might want to drop the hearing procedures, but that the more serious delays in evictions are in the court system and would not be changed. <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said laws in some states do not appear to provide enough protection for tenants in eviction cases to meet <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> guidelines for waiving the formal hearing procedures. The proposal to fence in housing projects will be controversial and likely will be rejected in most cases, according to <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, whose organization represents 90 percent of the local public housing agencies that operate federally subsidized housing. He said a main concern of public housing agencies is making projects blend in with the surrounding neighborhoods, and fencing would only make them stand out and be even more attractive to drug activity by outsiders. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> acknowledged on Monday that fences may not work in all cases and said they should be considered on a case-by-case basis. `` A security fence may be different from barbed wire,'' <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said. `` We're not trying to keep people in. We're trying to get drug users from getting in.'' In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, housing authorities have no plans to require residents to have photo identification cards or to surround projects with fences, said <PERSON> Val </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, spokesman for the city housing authority. He called the steps `` draconian.'' `` We're not that demoralized,'' <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s need is for more money _ to increase its public housing authority police force and to provide job training for tenants. But some other cities, including <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, have already begun issuing photo identification cards in certain cases, such as for tenants of high-rise and senior-citizen projects. Mayor <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION>, praised <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>'s enthusiasm and said most of his suggestions could be useful. But he cautioned that increasing security in projects may only move drug problems into surrounding areas unless broader programs are provided to poor urban residents.
