<FIRST>r w PM-WaterFight     04-12 0716</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Water Fight,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Renewing California Water Leases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, although conceding possible environmental problems, is renewing long-term water leases to farmers in central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in an attempt to put to rest an emotional fight over federal water in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. The controversy over water distribution to central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> farmers has been marked by disagreement within the administration for months. Environmentalists have characterized the outcome as another barometer on the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's desire to protect the environment and natural resources. The <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which issues the leases, has favored automatic renewal, while the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> has argued that a formal environmental assessment should first be made. The president's <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> is planning to review the matter Thursday. But Interior Secretary <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, announced Tuesday that he has decided to renew the first lease to come before the department, committing federal water to the Orange Cove Irrigation District in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joaquin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> for another 40 years. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> said the decision would not affect the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> council's proceedings. The council has no authority to block the leases or order a formal environmental impact statement, although its views historically have been given considerable weight by agencies and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` This decision further corrodes the environmental credentials of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration,'' said Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on water, power and offshore energy resources While the lease renewal announced Tuesday involves only one of a number of central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> irrigation projects, it was viewed widely as an indication of how the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> likely will deal with future renewal cases as other long-term leases expire. Environmentalists have opposed renewal of the long-term leases because the commitment locks the government into supplying a certain volume of water to farmers well into the next century at a time when rapid population growth is creating new, non-farm water demands. As water continues to be diverted for both agriculture and urban use, streams will dry up and seasonal wetlands, which support migratory waterfowl, will disappear, the critics maintain. The leases provide for water delivered through the Friant Unit of the Central Valley Project, a massive central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> irrigation system, that each year provides 1.5 billion acre feet of federal water to central <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> farms and orchards through an elaborate system of dams and canals. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> in a statement conceded that the long-term leases `` may pose legitimate environmental concerns.'' But he said those concerns could be resolved by state and local officials. He directed the chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reclamation </ORGANIZATION> to conduct an environmental assessment and provide it to those officials for consideration so the state and local officials may then `` adopt environmentally sensitive operating procedures and water policies.'' But <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanderson </PERSON>, director of the office of federal activities at the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, suggested <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON>'s procedures for dealing with environmental concerns amount to `` sidestepping'' the National Environmental Policy Act under which environmentalists had sought to get a formal environmental impact statement, or <ORGANIZATION> EIS </ORGANIZATION>, before any leases were renewed. The environmental review directed by <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> `` is essentially different than doing an <ORGANIZATION> EIS </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Sanderson </PERSON> in an interview. `` Our position -LRB- at <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is the entire water issue for <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> needs to be reviewed in light of today's environmental standards and particularly the environmental requirements 40 years hence,'' <PERSON> Sanderson </PERSON> added. <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> Block </PERSON>, an attorney who represents several environmental groups including the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in challenging the lease renewals in a lawsuit filed in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, accused <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> of `` undermining the procedures'' established to deal with the environmental concerns. `` It's kind of backward to sign the leases and then order and environmental assessment,'' <PERSON> Block </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Lujan </PERSON> suggested that the issuance of the one lease renewal would not affect the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> environmental council's review of the broader environmental issues involving all of the upcoming leases. He also said the Orange Cove lease would encourage increased water conservation among the farmers by charging `` substantially higher prices'' for the water. Under the new contract with <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cove </LOCATION>, the cost of federal water would quadruple from $ 3.50 to $ 14.94 per acre foot, he said. An acre foot is an amount of water need to flood an acre of land one foot deep, or about 350,000 gallons.
