<FIRST>r w PM-FairnessDoctrine     04-12 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fairness Doctrine,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Clears Bill Restoring Fairness Doctrine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee's vote to impose a new fairness doctrine on broadcasters sets the stage for a confrontation with the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and a probable <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> challenge. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> issued the challenge Tuesday when on a voice vote it approved a fairness doctrine bill introduced by committee chairman Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich. The bill goes to the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, where it is expected to pass easily. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has told <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> that it will urge President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to veto any fairness doctrine law that passes <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoed an identical bill in 1987, the same year the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> repealed its doctrine on the grounds it violated the First Amendment and no longer served the public interest in an era of diverse media outlets. The 50-year-old rules required broadcasters to air opposing views of controversial issues. If the bill should pass both houses of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and become law, a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> test also would seem likely because of what opponents say is the doctrine's unconstitutional infringement on broadcasters' rights. A federal appeals court earlier this year ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> had the authority to scrap the doctrine, but the court sidestepped the issue of the doctrine's constitutionality. Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on telecommunications and finance, said the fairness doctrine is not a great burden on broadcasters and only assures `` more speech'' on public issues The bill would not impose criminal sanctions on broadcasters who violate the doctrine, <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said, adding that a station never has lost its license for fairness doctrine infractions. The committee's ranking Republican, Rep. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Lent </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said the bill is designed to provide `` a minimal assurance of fair play.'' Opponents included Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, who said, `` This is a clear violation of the First Amendment.'' He also disputed the view that broadcasters must be required to be fair because they are licensed to exploit a `` scarce'' medium _ the airwaves. `` Our founding fathers had the question before them: ` Do we want a fair press or do we want a free press?' And they made the choice that we ought to have a free press,'' <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON> said. `` There were at that time very few media outlets in the nation,'' he said. `` And of course then as today it was abundantly clear that some of those media outlets sometimes engaged in activities which were perceived, may actually have been, unfair. But the founding fathers said there was a greater risk in attempting to control the media by imposing fairness than there is in permitting a free media to perhaps occasionally be unfair.'' The fairness doctrine has been opposed by many broadcasters, particularly smaller station owners who say the threat of lawsuits is enough to make them just play music instead of discussing controversial issues.
</TEXT>
