<HEAD>Fire Injures Two, Causes Evacuations and Power Outage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A spectacular five-alarm fire Tuesday destroyed a roofing materials warehouse, forced the evacuation of nearby buildings and injured two warehouse workers slightly, firefighters said. The blaze sent a towering column of smoke over the suburban area between <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>, knocked out electricity to downtown <ORGANIZATION> Auburn </ORGANIZATION> and snarled traffic as stoplights went dark and motorists slowed for a glimpse of the flames. Four other buildings in an area of more than 100,000 square feet also were engulfed in flames. An undetermined number of people were evacuated from four nearby businesses, and firefighters hosed down a house across the street that was threatened by the flames. No firefighters were hurt, although shifting winds blew sparks and flaming tarpaper around the <ORGANIZATION> Leatherback </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> warehouse. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> DeHart </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Kent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the smoke could pose a threat to area residents with respiratory problems. Most of the smoke was blown to the south, but some stayed in the area. The fire apparently started around 2:30 p.m. near an electrical panel, but the cause remained undetermined, authorities said. Damage initially was estimated at about $ 1 million. Fire officials estimated it would take the 75 firefighters from five jurisdictions at least 12 hours to extinguish. The building contained large amounts of felt paper and tar to make tarpaper for roofing, said an <ORGANIZATION> Auburn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman who refused to give his name. `` It's hot and it's nasty,'' he said. Asphalt stored at 300 to 400 degrees in the warehouse had only to get a bit too hot to burst into flames, he said. Two Leatherback workers were treated for minor burns after trying to extinguish the fire earlier in the day, officials said. The blaze spread despite a sprinkler system, and the two workers and nine other employees fled, workers said. Several tanks of industrial chemicals exploded. Firefighters tried to prevent flames from reaching a 61,000-gallon tank of liquid asphalt and a large propane tank.
