<FIRST>r w PM-RuralPoverty     04-12 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rural Poverty,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Says Rural and Inner-City Poverty Rates are Similar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Country people were just as poor during the economic recovery as they were during the last decade's recession, according to a study that found little difference between urban and rural poverty. The study, Poverty in <LOCATION> Rural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>: A National Overview, said more than one in six people in rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> fell below the federal poverty line of $ 9,056 for a family of three in 1987 while the rate was one in eight for residents of metropolitan areas during that year. `` In fact, the rural poverty rate for 1987 _ the fifth year of an economic recovery _ was as high as the rate for 1975, the deepest recession year of the 1970s,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> and Policy Priorities, while presenting the study Tuesday to a hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION>, Youth and Families. Using data from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> on poverty from 1978 to 1987, the Center for Budget and Policy Priorities found that the rural poverty rate rose from 13.5 percent to 16.9 percent. In metropolitan areas during the same period, the rate rose from 10.4 percent to 12.5 percent. Metropolitan areas comprise one or more cities and their suburbs. In the central cities, which frequently are associated with poverty, the rate climbed from 15.4 percent to 18.6 percent, according to the study. `` What's most striking is that the rate of poverty in rural areas is almost as high as in central cities,'' <PERSON> Greenstein </PERSON> said Tuesday in an interview. The center, a nonprofit organization which conducts research and analysis on a range of public policy issues concerning low-income families and individuals, found the changes in poverty consistent among most racial, ethnic, age and demographic groups. The rural poor are more likely to be white because there is a lower proportion of minorities in nonmetropolitan areas, but `` more than two-fifths -LRB- 44.1 percent -RRB- of nonmetro blacks were poor in 1987, compared to one-third -LRB- 33.3 percent -RRB- of blacks living in central cities.'' There also were more poor elderly people living in rural than urban areas, the study said. The only segment of the rural poor that was smaller than its urban counterpart was children. According to the study, 23.1 percent of rural children were poor while 29.6 percent of the children in the central cities were poor in 1987. But one feature that distinguished the rural poor from their urban counterparts is that rural poverty is likely to occur in two-parent families where one or both parents work. `` Nearly two of every three poor families living in rural areas contained at least one worker in 1987,'' the study said. `` Nearly one quarter had at least two workers.''
</TEXT>
