<HEAD>Pakistan Agrees To Four U.N. Border Checkposts in Afghanistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has agreed to allow four <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> checkpoints on its border with <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> following an exchange of charges and denials at an emergency meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s Marxist government and its ally the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> claim <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is violating international accords by aiding Afghan guerrillas. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has denied the allegations but announced Tuesday at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> that it would allow <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> checkpoints in <LOCATION> Chaman </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Parachinar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Torkham </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nawa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pass </LOCATION>. Most <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> diplomats said the few checkpoints would not stem the tide of infiltration across the border. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> has just 50 military observers in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s government had allowed them to roam the border at will but not set up checkpoints. Afghan Foreign Minister <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> called for <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> checkpoints amd urged the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to send a mission to the region to investigate his claim that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is committing aggression against <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. He accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of waging `` full-fledged war'' and called for an international conference to safeguard <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s sovereignty He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, as co-guarantors of a U.N.-mediated Afghan accord, should persuade <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> to halt its support of the Afghan insurgents. <PERSON> Iqbal </PERSON> <PERSON> Akhund </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Pakistani </LOCATION> foreign affairs official, called the Afghan charges a fabrication. But he told the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has agreed to provide a permanent presence along the border to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assistance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> for <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Then he added: `` Peace and stability in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> can be restored only if power is transferred from the illegal <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> regime to a broad-based government acceptable to the Afghan people.'' The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> sent troops into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 to help the government battle the guerrillas and eventually had more than 100,000 military personnel in the country. Under the U.N.-sponsored accord, the Soviets accepted a withdrawal plan and said the last of its troops had pulled out as of Feb. 15. Millions of Afghan refugees fled into <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> over the past decade and the major Afghan rebel groups established their bases along the frontier. The <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, meeting in response to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s complaint, heard only Afghan and Pakistani speakers The meeting was adjourned and another session was to be scheduled after consultations among the 15 council members. No resolution is expected because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is an ally of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and helps support the rebels. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> could be expected to veto any measure critical of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> accused <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> of numerous attacks and of involving its forces in fighting in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, including the battle for the city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION> near the Pakistani border. He also claimed <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is arming and training Afghan rebels and has established 125 training centers on Afghan soil in violation of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> accords. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> signed the pact in April 1988. It provides for the withdrawal of the Soviet forces and non-interference in the other country's internal affairs. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> signed as guarantors, but both have continued supplying their respective sides. <PERSON> Wakil </PERSON> did not directly criticize the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> but said: `` The question is why the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a big world power, becomes the tool for the implementation of Pakistani policies on <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and why should the strategic interests of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> be subordinated to the expansionist designs of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> in the region.''
