<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Debt,0624</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Signs $3.6 Billion Debt Assistance Agreement With IMF</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has signed a $ 3.65 billion three-year loan agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> to bolster the country's foreign exchange reserves and help spur domestic economic growth. The accord breaks from previous <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> practice by mandating no new austerity measures, said <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, struggling to overcome the burden of payments to commercial banks and governments on its $ 107 billion foreign debt, is the developing world's second-largest debtor. Only <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> owes more _ $ 121 billion. Tuesday's agreement is the first from the international lending community since <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> outlined a debt-reduction plan on March 10 that he hoped would help ease payment terms on the developing world's $ 1.32 trillion foreign debt. As interest rates have risen worldwide since last year, the higher rates have created additional problems for countries struggling to meet the terms of payments to foreign creditors. Some debtor nations threaten default unless they can arrive at more favorable terms with lenders. Austerity measures imposed by the Venezuelan government at the behest of international lending organizations prompted riots last month in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION> that led to the deaths of more than 300 people. <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said Tuesday that his country's agreement intends to reverse <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s net outflow of funds and provide investment money to spur economic growth, which was nil last year. By stipulating that the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> recognizes <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s need to set its growth priorities first and schedule debt servicing accordingly, <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said the agreement `` is a fundamental change from the past.'' `` The agreement reached with the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> constitutes a plain endorsement of the economic strategy of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>,'' he said. That means the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> will not require further devaluations of the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> peso, as has been called for in previous agreements in an effort to stimulate exports, said one government official on condition of anonymity. President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortarihas </PERSON> pressed efforts to cut the outflow of capital needed to revitalize <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s stagnant economy. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has been expected to be among the first beneficiaries of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plan, which seeks to entice banks to forgive part of the debt in return for assurances from the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> that the remaining debt will be paid. <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> also announced that <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will conclude an agreement this week with the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> for $ 1.5 billion in credits to support the government's restructuring programs. In addition, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> shortly expects to obtain $ 500 million in compensatory financing from the fund, <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said. The combined credits `` will be devoted to operations that reduce the debt and its servicing,'' he said. On April 19, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will formally present creditor banks its proposals to reduce the foreign debt's value, cut servicing and obtain additional lending over several years, the treasury chief said. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will offer banks the option of exchanging old debt for Mexican bonds that discount debt principal and reduce interest rates, <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> told the private `` 24 Hours'' newscast late Tuesday. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> netted a $ 1.1 billion reduction of debt principal in a bond auction backed by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Treasury last year. <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> agreement also will promote <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s efforts to reach restructuring agreements with the <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> of creditor government banks. He stressed that Tuesday's pact `` is a new type of agreement that bolsters a strategy of sustained economic growth with price stability,'' a clear reference to <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON>' anti-inflation program. That program has reduced inflation from a record 159.2 percent in 1987 to 52.7 percent in 1988. The government predicts inflation will reach 18 percent this year.
