ON> Hollywood </LOCATION> and Madison Avenue in making drinking and driving as socially passe as smoking cigarettes. Last year, <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> researchers made a low-key appeal to television executives to write in occasional references to designated drivers. The proposal was endorsed by the board of the Writer's Guild of <LOCATION> America-West </LOCATION>. Having characters casually refer to picking a designated driver, someone who stays sober to drive the drinkers home, reinforces what is already becoming accepted partying behavior, <PERSON> Winsten </PERSON> said. `` Our role really is as a catalyst,'' he said. `` Producers, like the public, they're primed and ready to respond to this issue.'' The message was broadcast in various ways this season. On one episode of CBS' `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>,'' a bedraggled <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ewing </PERSON> explains to his young son that he could n't drive home the night before because he'd been drinking. Of course, <PERSON> J.R. </PERSON> is n't telling the whole truth about his nocturnal adventures, but the message is clear. On <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Family Ties,'' <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Keaton </PERSON>, the character played by <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, visits a restaurant with a tank of live fish. When a member of the group is soaked in a mishap in the tank, <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> is asked to take her home. He responds by saying he is the designated driver, but had expected to drive home someone who drank like a fish, not someone who was hit by a fish. The `` Growing Pains'' episode revolves around <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Seaver </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Tracey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and her boyfriend, <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON>, who is seriously injured in an auto accident after drinking at a college hangout. `` What we hope to achieve is, I guess, just an