<HEAD>Embattled Superintendent's Contract Renewed Amid Controversy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto BX13 of April 11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The city's first black school chief hung on to his job by one vote, but opponents of <LOCATION> Laval </LOCATION> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> vowed to continue working to oust him. Bitterness from the 7-6 vote Tuesday night by the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> spilled over to the announcement that <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s contract would be renewed. As committee President <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON> tried to move on to other agenda items after the announcement, committee member <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cappucci </PERSON> suddenly took command of the microphone. `` We're going to do everything in our power to see to it that we get a new superintendent,'' <PERSON> Cappucci </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said he was delighted with the renewal but acknowledged there had been problems during his tenure. `` I do n't think anyone was expecting a real endorsement,'' the 53-year-old <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> native said after the announcement. `` The issue was whether or not we could continue the progress we've made.'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s arrival in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> four years ago to operate the country's oldest public school system was heralded as the healing of racial wounds that had festered since the first days of federally ordered desegregation in the mid-1970s. But the honeymoon has come to an end in recent months, with critics increasingly denouncing what they call <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s `` autocratic'' style Committee member <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Nucci </PERSON>, who supports <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, said it was everyone's duty to try to make the uneasy union work. `` I hope they realize that personal vendetta have to be put aside in the interest of the school system,'' he said. `` We have to think of the kids first.'' But <PERSON> Cappucci </PERSON> said he and other diss