<HEAD>Tom Bradley: `Teflon Mayor' Wins Fifth Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-LA Mayor, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For Mayor <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, called the `` Teflon mayor'' because the blame for the city's problems has n't stuck to him in the past, the timing for a re-election bid could n't have been much worse. Gang-related murders are on the rise, traffic congestion is horrendous, the sewage system is failing and there's problems with smog, housing and homelessness. The 71-year-old <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' first black mayor, won election to an unprecedented fifth term Tuesday but by a far less of a margin than published polls had predicted. Early today, he held more than 52 percent of the vote with 98.4 percent of the city's precincts reporting. He needed at least 50 percent to avoid a June 6 runoff. His nine rivals were not well known and voter turnout was less than 20 percent. A recent poll by the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> showed 78 percent of Hispanics, 70 percent of whites and 68 percent of blacks had a favorable impression of the Democratic mayor. Pollsters had said that <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>'s low-key image helped him. <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON>, mayor for 16 years, a city councilman and a policeman before that, may be one of the most private public persons in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. `` There's a mystery about him that I do n't know if anyone will ever crack,'' former press deputy <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> once said. `` I've spent more time with him than anyone, including his wife, during the I still do n't understand him.'' His political powers as mayor include an ability to heal his wounds almost overnight and a quick recovery when he slips. He's slipped twice in runs for governor. In his first try, he lost to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> in 1982 by just 1.2 percent. Some said voter racism shaved the ballots <PERSON> Bradley </P