/LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> fell to Communist forces in April 1975. In the joint field missions, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> and Vietnamese investigators interview villagers and inspect <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warplane crash sites to try to resolve `` discrepancy cases'' that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> considers top priority. These are cases that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say Vietnamese authorities should have information on, including cases of airmen who survived crashes but failed to emerge from prisoner of war camps. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> previously announced that <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> on April 27 would return 21 sets of remains that may be those of missing Americans. <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has returned large numbers of remains since August 1987, when it agreed to accelerate cooperation on the issue in return for <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s help in encouraging private humanitarian aid to <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>. More than 1,700 Americans are listed as missing in action in <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and others are unaccounted for in <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The pro-Vietnamese government in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> claims to have found the remains of some of the 83 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen missing there, but a senior <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> official last week there was `` no progress'' in arranging their repatriation. <PERSON> Uch </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiman </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, repeated his government's demand that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government receive the remains directly and not through intermediaries. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> has refused to do that and instead has requested assistance from an international organization because it does not recognize the government, which <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> installed after invading the country in late 1978. `` There should be negotiations between governments, not between this government and private groups,'' <PERSON> Uch </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiman </PERSON> said in an interview in <LOCATION> Phnom </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Penh </LOCATION> with two <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> journalists. `` We do n't seem to have a positive signal from the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> government ... regarding the return of the remains of the MIAs,'' he said. In February, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> told a former American aid official that about 10 percent of the 83 Americans listed as MIA have been found.
