pvs, The four women.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury considering the bribery case against three <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> executives charged in the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> corruption case resumed deliberations today after failing to reach a verdict in two days. The four women and eight men informed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> late Tuesday that they had not come to a decision after a total of 20 hours of deliberations. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said he would give the jury new instructions today if they were having problems with the charges. <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Schnittjer </PERSON>, <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaub </PERSON>, three former vice presidents of <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Newbury </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, are charged with bribery, conspiracy and wire fraud in the first case brought to trial since the government `` Ill Wind'' investigation into fraud and kickbacks at the Pentagon began nearly three years ago. Kaub is also charged with two counts of filing false statements. The case involves what prosecutors say was a conspiracy to bribe a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> official for information about a $ 24 million contract that <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> obtained in July 1987 to build hand-held radar test sets. The government claims the defendants knew that <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON>, a private consultant hired by <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION>, was paying bribes to <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Berlin </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> official. Both <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, as well as <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION>, the parent of <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION>, have pleaded guilty in the case and are cooperating with government. But the defendants said they did n't know <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> had done anything illegal. Kaub, <PERSON> Schnittjer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> testified <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> was hired for $ 10,000 for his expertise in November 1985. He was promised $ 150,000 if <ORGANIZATION> Teledyne </ORGANIZATION> won the radar contract, which it did. <PERSON> Parkin </PERSON> was paid about $ 18,000 before the payments stopped when the Ill Wind case was made public.
