<HEAD>Doctor Suspended At Austrian Hospital Where Patients Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City authorities today suspended the director of the hospital department where four assistant nurses have confessed to killing at least 49 patients in the past six years. The suspension followed mounting criticism of the chief doctor's conduct during a police investigation last year at <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Lainz </LOCATION> hospital, where elderly patients reportedly were killed by overdoses of medicine or by forcing water into their lungs Senior police investigator <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON> said Monday that police met `` a wall of silence'' at the hospital during the probe. A police report says the department head, Dr. <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> had declined to give police the name of a second doctor, who alerted <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> to suspicions about the killings after talking with a Chilean-born nurse's assistant. The four assistant nurses claim they engaged in `` mercy killings,'' but police said the methods they used made that motive unlikely. The Neue <ORGANIZATION> Kronen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeitung </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s largest circulation tabloid, said today that if <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> and the second doctor `` had not kept quiet, it would fairly certainly have been possible to stop the series of murders a year ago. `` As it was, however, the sadistic nurses could kill another 22 people,'' the newspaper added. Police have not confirmed media reports that 22 of the 49 people killed were slain in the last year alone. Mayor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Zilk </PERSON> said he was suspending <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON>, head of the first medical department at <LOCATION> Lainz </LOCATION> hospital, `` on the grounds of the results to date of the police investigations.'' He declined further comment. <PERSON> Alois </PERSON> <PERSON> Stacher </PERSON>, chief of the city's health department, said <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> was suspended because of `` lingering lack of clarity'' over the investigation. <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> consistently has defended his role in the investigation and the conduct of officials in his department at the <LOCATION> Lainz </LOCATION> hospital, <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s fourth largest, since the first word of the killings on Friday. The doctor and other hospital officials declined comment today. The Chilean-born nurse's assistant, <PERSON> Dorah </PERSON> <PERSON> Eugenie </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrada-Avendano </PERSON>, was questioned by police Tuesday and arrested after she admitted to witnessing one of the killings, <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON> said. But he told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> he would try to free the woman because `` she has really helped the police.'' Ms. <PERSON> Ferrada-Avendano </PERSON> knew of killings at the hospital two or three years before she told the unidentified doctor of her suspicions last year, <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON> said on television Tuesday. He described her as a single parent who as a foreigner was afraid of losing her job if she went to police. A former patient at the hospital who knows the woman, now an Austrian citizen, told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> she feared political persecution if forced to return to <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>. Assistant nurses <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Gruber </PERSON>, 25, <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> Leidorf </PERSON>, 27, and <PERSON> Waltraud </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, 30, have been in custody since Friday. <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON> was detained Sunday. None of the women has been charged. Police said the four women confessed they killed at least 49 patients and that Ms. <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> admitted killing 39 of them. Pesendorfer is the first doctor or official suspended because of the mass killings.
