<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with guerrillas rejecting interrogation;
new police quotes. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WINDHOEK, Namibia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Namibian guerrilla leader today rejected <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s plan to interrogate insurgents who report to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers to be escorted back to bases in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. By midday today, territorial police said no guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> South-West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Africa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> had shown up at any of nine checkpoints established Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> force monitoring <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>'s transition to independence. `` It is not the business of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> to interrogate or check <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> cadres. It the business of UNTAG and UNTAG alone,'' guerrilla official <PERSON> Kapuka </PERSON> <PERSON> Nauyala </PERSON> said today of the U.N. Transition Assistance Group. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nujoma </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>'s exiled president, has called on his fighters to withdraw as part of an agreement to get the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> independence plan back on track after heavy fighting last week. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> says about 1,900 guerrillas infiltrated into northern <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> starting April 1, the day a cease-fire was to take hold. <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> investigators agree the guerrillas violated a peace accord requiring they stay in Angolan bases at least until May 15. Territorial officials said Tuesday the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> had agreed that police supervised by <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peacekeepers could interrogate guerrillas who report to the checkpoints about the whereabouts of other insurgents and possible arms caches. But a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official, speaking on condition of anonymity, no such agreement was reached. <PERSON> Nauyala </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION>'s chief representative in <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, said any questioning by security forces would be unacceptable. `` UNTAG will commit a monumental sin if it allows itself to be co-opted into <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s campaign aimed at discrediting and humiliating <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> and its military cadres,'' <PERSON> Nauyala </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> Zimbabwe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inter-African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. Black African nations last week denounced the special <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> envoy to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Martti </PERSON> <PERSON> Ahtisaari </PERSON>, who outraged them by allowing South Africa-led security forces out of bases to fight the guerrilla incursion. White security force officers and Namibian civilians who support <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> predict few guerrillas will report to the checkpoints. They cite the deployment of security force personnel at the points, the proximity of military bases, and poor communication between guerrilla commanders and their forces. Police said some guerrillas might try to cross into <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> without reporting to checkpoints and others might hide their weapons, don civilian clothes and try to stay in <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. Police Chief Inspector <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Brune </PERSON> said groups of insurgents were seen today moving south, away from the <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> border. No major skirmishes have been reported since last weekend. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> says 263 guerrillas and 27 security force members were killed in fighting that erupted April 1. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> says 38 of its fighters and 54 civilians were killed. Another 15 guerrillas were captured. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> has ruled the mineral-rich territory north of its border since World War I and in defiance of <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> demands it withdraw. In December, <LOCATION> Pretoria </LOCATION> agreed to give <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> independence in exchange for <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> withdrawing its 50,000 troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, where they supported the Marxist government's forces in a civil war against rebels backed by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> SWAPO </ORGANIZATION> has been fighting South African rule since 1966.
