 April 7 The <LOCATION> Duluth </LOCATION> -LRB- Minn. -RRB- News-Tribune on President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s education proposals: President ... <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposals for education might be considered too modest by his political opponents and too varied by those who can only see education dollars in terms of teacher salaries, but the program he outlined -LRB- last -RRB- week represents a solid, progressive start in improving <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> education. It is positively radical compared with his predecessor's inclinations for federal education programs -LRB- <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> -RRB- wants to spend $ 423 million on such things as grants for successful schools, scholarships for students who excel in math and science, and funding of magnet schools to expand parental choice. Other efforts would put more non-teachers in classrooms, set up anti-drug programs, reward excellent teachers and help <PERSON> black </PERSON> colleges build up endowments. Nothing is settled at this point. The funding will no doubt undergo changes as <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> deliberates these and other measures, but, given the constraints imposed by deficits, there is every reason to be optimistic about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plans for education.
