<TEXT>
 April 10 The Patriot, <LOCATION> Harrisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, on the Soviet elections: The recent voting for members to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies was the first relatively open election held in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 70 years And remarkable as it may seem, given our far greater experience at democracy, the Soviet election may have something instructive to offer the American political system. Whether the elected People's Deputies get to exercise any degree of power remains to be seen. Nevertheless, the stunning number of high and mighty who were defeated dealt what The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> headlined was `` a mortifying blow to party officials.'' The magnitude of the revolt was made extraordinary by the substantial number of candidates who were defeated even though they ran without opposition. Voters were able to cross out the name of unopposed candidates and thus register a `` no'' vote. If Americans could vote `` none of the above'' or against an unopposed candidate, we suspect many more would go to the polls. The question is: Would our politicians dare to give the people the option of voting for none of the above?
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 April 7 <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Tupelo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, on Polish elections: The march of democracy continues. It's enough to make <PERSON> Vladamir </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON> ... spin his tomb. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> -LRB- has -RRB- announced ... that the government and the outlawed labor union Solidarity have reached an accord that will make free elections possible again. Poles have not voted in democratic elections since 1945. The first ballot this year is guaranteed to give the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> almost a two-thirds majority, but the agreement throws the electoral process wide open in subsequent elections. Few people besides the democrats in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, like Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, thought this day would come. But it's also true that few people, at least in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, thought they ever would see Russians able to vote for anything that resembles a democratic ballot. Soviets, some of them within sight of <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>'s tomb in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, voted in open elections three weeks ago. The West, led by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, ca n't be a Pollyana in the face of rapid changes. But neither can any peace-loving Western nation overlook opportunities to defuse world tensions and make additional democratic reforms attractive to the East.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 April 4 <LOCATION> Corvallis </LOCATION> -LRB- Ore. -RRB- Gazette-Times on drift-net fishing: There's good reason for calling drift-net fishing `` strip mining of the sea.'' An Asian fleet of 1,000 to 1,500 vessels deploys as many as 30,000 miles of drift net each day. Floating 30 feet down from the ocean surface, the fine-meshed nylon nets catch not only fish and squid, but everything else they encounter _ dolphins, whales, birds and sea lions. Perhaps even worse, the nets are inefficient, wasting about half the catch that is killed but then lost overboard. ... Under the Drift Net Impact Monitoring Assessment and Control Act of 1987, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has been negotiating with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> to place observers on their ships to determine just how damaging drift-net fishing is. ... -LRB- T -RRB- he immediate task facing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is to get its observers onto the Asian drift-net vessels. ... <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiators must make it clear to the <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> governments that this country is serious about ... sanctions.
