anager, new party rules stripped <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> members of the automatic delegate status for future conventions and instituted proportional representation as the basis for selecting delegates. Still, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> contended that minimum-vote requirements resulted in denying him a proportion of delegates equal to the popular vote he received. He also viewed the party and elected officials sent to the convention, as uncommitted super delegates, as a force largely opposed to his candidacy. Only a handful of elected officials backed <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s bid for the presidential nomination. `` I have absolutely no intention to appoint, empower or create any kind of rules commission,'' said <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, at a news conference at which he announced the appointments of senior <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION> staff. `` We do n't win or lose elections because of rules. ... I frankly think it would be foolhardy for this party to spend the next two years in a bloody and divisive fight over the rules,'' he said. After presidential election defeats in 1968, 1972 and 1980, the Democrats engaged in sweeping revisions of the party rules. After the 1984 defeat, the party went through a more modest change. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> also said recent Democratic election victories in contests to fill vacant House seats were of `` tremendous national significance.'' Democrat <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON> was an upset victor in the contest to fill the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> seat in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> once held by Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. The Democrats also held a Democratic seat in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and are given a good chance of capturing the <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION> seat formerly held by <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON>