<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 First lady <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> underwent radioactive treatment today to destroy her thyroid gland because it is producing excess levels of hormones, a condition that has irritated her eyes and caused her to lose 18 pounds in recent months. `` She's just fine, piece of cake, never broke her stride,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s press secretary, <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, said after the president's wife returned to the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> following a two-hour stay at <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. The radiation was administered in an iodine solution sipped through a straw. Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said it was a colorless liquid that tasted like water, Ms. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> reported. Doctors told Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, 63, that the only side effect she may suffer is a slight pain in the neck for several days. `` She cracked jokes about that all day,'' Ms. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said. Moreover, `` just as a precaution, she should n't hug her puppies for a couple of days and she should n't kiss her grandchildren,'' the spokeswoman said. She explained that puppies and children have a heightened sensitivity to the radiation in Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s body. The first lady has 11 grandchildren and her dog, <PERSON> Millie </PERSON>, recently produced six puppies. Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> expressed surprise that her treatment attracted so much news media attention, and was `` wondering why her visit to <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Reed </PERSON> gets so much coverage when <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Help </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- a non-profit organization for youngsters -RRB- does n't,'' her press secretary said. A White House statement said the procedure `` has no significant side effects'' and has been a standard treatment for 40 years for people suffering with Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s condition, known as Graves disease. Once her thyroid gland has stopped operating, probably in two to three months, Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will have to take daily medication to maintain adequate hormone levels, Ms. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was asked about his wife at a White House ceremony for the college basketball champions while Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was still at the hospital. He replied `` Fine,'' when asked how she was doing. Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> consulted doctors last month because of swelling and irritation in her eyes, causing them to tear, and the sudden weight loss. For several weeks, Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been treated with methimazole, a drug that blocks production of excess hormones in the thyroid, a butterfly-shaped gland in the neck. Ms. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> said the use of drugs was an interim therapy and that the destruction of the thyroid through radiation was a more permanent treatment. Left untreated, Graves disease can be life-threatening, but it generally responds quickly to therapy. It is caused when antibodies attack the thyroid gland and cause it to secrete too much hormone. The disease is more apt to occur in older women. Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s treatment with methimazole was discontinued Sunday in preparation for today's procedure. It will be restarted three days after the treatment and then continue until her level of thyroid hormones falls below normal. Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is under the care of <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> physicians <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohr </PERSON>, in consultation with Dr. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Burman </PERSON>, a thyroid specialist at <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reed </ORGANIZATION>.
