<HEAD>Activist Says Wheat Outlook Shaky, and Looking Worse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A consumer advocate said Wednesday that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat outlook is so shaky that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should suspend further export subsidies until the situation improves. <PERSON> Rodney </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>, executive director of the private, non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said he wrote <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> on April 3 to repeat a similar request made last fall, `` when the situation was less precarious'' and steps `` could have been taken to safeguard supplies.'' The target of <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>'s complaint is the Export Enhancement Program, which subsidizes the sale of wheat and other commodities to selected foreign countries. Huge sales of wheat to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> have been made under the program since the arrangement was authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the 1985 farm law. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said this week the program had helped significantly in getting agricultural trade discussions moving under the current <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade. But <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> also said in an interview with a group of reporters on Monday that the subsidy program would be reviewed to see how effective it has been and whether `` too much or too little'' is being spent on it. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said that the condition of the winter wheat crop is deteriorating and that experts in the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and in the major production areas point to a harvest this year of about 1.6 billion bushels. A spring wheat output of 600 million bushels would make a total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat harvest of about 2.2 billion bushels. If wheat use in the 1989-90 marketing year, which will begin June 1, totals in the range of 2.4 billion to 2.5 billion bushels, this year's harvest would fall short of meeting demand. In that case, <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said in his letter to <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, at least 200 million bushels of wheat will have to be drawn from existing stocks, which are estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to be drawn down to 549 million bushels by June 1. Thus, he said, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat stockpile by June 1, 1990, could well be down to around 300 million bushels. According to department records, that would be the the smallest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat reserve at the end of a marketing year since 1952, when it was 256 million bushels. `` This is hardly adequate as a domestic reserve, and will leave the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unable to intervene if famine conditions develop anywhere in the world,'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> said. `` The -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- Food and <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> ... a month ago said that world grain stocks will be drawn down again in 1989-90 for the third year in a row.'' <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> added: `` In effect, <ORGANIZATION> FAO </ORGANIZATION> does not expect food grain production to increase significantly in any of the major food-producing areas outside the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>'' The department's first official estimate of 1989 winter wheat production, which usually accounts for three-fourths of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> total, will be released May 11. Meanwhile, department analysts have used unofficial projections showing that the 1989 wheat harvest could be as low as 2.3 billion bushels, or slightly more than <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON>'s benchmark. The biggest problem is in major areas of the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, particularly in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, the No. 1 wheat producer, where soils have been parched since the crop was planted last fall. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> is scheduled to tour some of the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> wheat area on Friday, his office said. There has been congressional pressure on the department to extend 1988 drought relief to the stricken winter wheat farmers.
