<HEAD>Soviet Lawyer Asks for Review of New Decree on Subversion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leading lawyer called Wednesday for the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to review a new law on subversion, saying it may conflict with President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of glasnost. The decree appears to be aimed in part at stopping nationalist unrest like that in the republic of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>. It bans premeditated acts aimed at inciting nationalist or racial animosity and actions aimed at undermining the Soviet political and economic systems. Many dissidents have said the decree restricts freedom of speech and other human rights, but the criticism by <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> was the first made publicly by a Soviet lawyer. <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON>, a department head at the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> and Law, made the remarks at a news conference and in an article published Wednesday in the weekly newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. He said that in general, the decree was an improvement over earlier regulations banning `` anti-Soviet agitation and propaganda'' and `` anti-Soviet slander.'' Those rules have been used to jail dissidents. However, the lawyer said a section in the new rules on `` discrediting'' government bodies should be clarified. The clause says `` publicly insulting or discrediting'' government or state bodies or officials can be punishable by up to three years in prison or a fine of up to $ 3,200. <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> said his institute, part of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>, had drafted the decree. However, he said it was surprised by the clause. `` The regulation on insulting and discrediting was just as much news for us as for you,'' he told reporters. The lawyer said he did not know who inserted it into the decree, which was approved Saturday by the Presidium, or executive council, of the Supreme Soviet. The decree took effect Monday and will be reviewed later by the full legislature, which can make changes, <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> suggested the discrediting rule might conflict with glasnost, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of openness, because people should have the right to criticize their government. <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> called for `` urgent authoritative clarification'' of the clause by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The court can overturn the decree and send it back for revision if it is deemed unconstitutional. `` If an organ is discredited by true information that is revealed and objectively a loss of faith occurs as a result of unconstitutional, illegal or criminal actions, in that sense there can be no moral or criminal reproach,'' <PERSON> Yakovlev </PERSON> said. Another lawyer at the news conference, <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reshetnikov </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> All-Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> on Soviet Legislation, said the decree should have banned only false accusations.
