<HEAD>Council Finds No Compelling Need for Commercially Developed Platform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has no compelling need for a commercially developed space platform proposed for use before a larger planned space station is put into orbit, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> has concluded. A report by the council, released Tuesday, was based on a study by a panel of scientists and engineers. Its recommendations were counter to the proposal by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for heavy federal support for the commercial space platform. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> had opposed the proposed venture as a possible competitor with its own space station to be put in orbit by 1996. The report said there was no compelling need for a separate, commercially developed facility for the conduct of research at low or zero gravity before then. It said use of the space shuttle flights `` will accommodate the vast majority of anticipated experiments'' planned by <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> in the interim. It said after the space station is built, however, construction of another facility for long-term microgravity experiments `` may well have merit'' if there are advances in microgravity research and space automation. The report said the committee `` found no evidence to suggest that microgravity research would lead to significant space-based manufacturing in the next five to 10 years.'' `` The committee considers that microgravity science is at an immature stage due to lack of understanding of the fundamental processes involved in this area of space research,'' the report said. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's 1988 space policy recommended support for an orbiting spacecraft for microgravity research which would be owned and operated by private business rather than <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>. The federal government would be its main user, however, and would lease as much as 70 percent of the facility at a cost estimated at more than $ 700 million over five years. The proposal for the private platform was developed by <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, run by former <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> engineers and astronauts. It said its space platform could be launched as early as 1992. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> requested the council study the scientific and commercial benefits of the proposal. The council is an arm of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION>.
