<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on Wednesday approved a bill to reorganize the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and require studies, reports and decisions affecting a variety of products ranging from cigarette lighters to reclining chairs. The bill was sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> by the on commerce, consumer protection and competitiveness subcommittee on a voice vote after rejecting an amendment that would have renewed the commission's basic laws without change. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been unable to agree on such a renewal since 1983, and the commission has operated under automatic year-to-year renewals granted by appropriations bills. Last year, the parent committee approved a bill almost identical to the one passed by the subcommittee Wednesday, but it was too late in the session for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to act. Among major changes that would be made by the bill is the designation of two members as a quorum when there are only three members. Although the commission is authorized to have five members, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in recent years has appropriated money for only three salaries, and a current vacancy means the commission can not act at all because the quorum requirement is now three. The bill would require among other things: _ A study of flammability standards for pajamas and nightgowns used by the elderly _ A study of age requirements for operating amusement park rides _ A survey of reclining chairs for compliance with existing standards _ A report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on what the commission is doing about indoor air pollution _ The adoption of a standard for lighters to protect children The bill would also give state attorneys general the same power as the commission has to bring suits in federal courts and would permit consumers to petition for safety rules, with a 120-day deadline for action on such petitions. The bill is backed by major consumer organizations but opposed by major business groups. The author of the defeated amendment for a straightforward renewal, Rep. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nielson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, said, `` I do n't think there is any evidence the commission is not doing its job and I am particularly alarmed at the budget increase'' the bill would authorize. The bill would set a ceiling on appropriations of $ 39 million next year and $ 40 million the year after. <PERSON> Nielson </PERSON>'s amendment would have set ceilings of $ 34 million and $ 35 million; the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has recommended an appropriation of $ 33.5 million, down from $ 34.5 million this year. Deaths caused by products under the commission's jurisdiction have fallen from about 26,000 in 1975 to 22,000 in 1984, `` and the per capita decline has been more dramatic'' because the population has grown, <PERSON> Nielson </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think it's fair to the commission to put so many things in it -LRB- the bill -RRB- they ca n't handle,'' he said.
