<HEAD>Military Increases Pollution Inspections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has increased to more than 8,100 the number of military-base sites being surveyed for hazardous substances and pollution, according to a report send to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday. Actual cleanup work is going much more slowly, however. By the end of the past fiscal year, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> had projects under way at more than 1,260 polluted sites. The report, covering the year ending last Sept. 30, cites the jump in sites undergoing preliminary surveys as a development that demonstrates a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> commitment to restoring polluted areas under military control. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> made significant progress during fiscal 1988,'' the report says. It covers the efforts of <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> agencies and the military services to comply with a section of the Superfund law of 1986 that expanded the Defense Environmental Restoration Program. That program received $ 404 million in fiscal 1988. According to the report, 8,139 sites at 897 military installations had been identified for surveys by the end of the fiscal year to determine if a cleanup was needed. The totals at the end of the previous year had been 5,165 sites at 739 installations. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> attributed the jump to a desire to check `` primarily smaller installations such as <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> and Reserve properties'' after it had completed reviews of large, known problem areas around the country. The report further discloses that more than 4,400 sites have been moved into the next phase of the program, in which a more in-depth investigation is conducted and cleanup alternatives considered. That work has been completed only at about 1,500 of the sites, however. The third and final phase of the program _ actual cleanups _ is still moving at a relatively slow pace, the report indicates. As of the end of the fiscal year, actual cleanup work and `` remedial actions'' had been completed at 216 polluted sites _ a net gain of 90 compared to fiscal 1987. Cleanup work is under way at 1,266 other sites, the report states.
