PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `As the ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHLAND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A barge carrying the mammoth reactor vessel from the nation's first commercial nuclear plant completed an 8,000-mile trip today to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, where it will be buried at the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear complex. Protesters hurled paint canisters and unfurled banners as the reactor vessel from the dismantled <LOCATION> Shippingport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, nuclear plant made its way up the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in six-week journey that took it through the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION>. The barge arrived at a dock on the edge of <LOCATION> Richland </LOCATION>. The reactor vessel will be trucked 25 miles to the burial trench where it will be entombed Friday. <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION>, the government nuclear weapons complex, already is the final resting place for three nuclear submarine reactor cores. The 1,000-ton reactor vessel, 45 feet high and 18 feet across, once held the uranium fuel that powered the nation's first commercial nuclear plant, which shut down in 1982. The vessel was packed with concrete for the journey, and officials said it poses no threat of radiation. As the barge made its way up the <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gorge </LOCATION> on Tuesday, 50 to 70 protesters on a bridge waved banners and signs and hurled canisters of lime green paint. At least three small containers of paint were hurled from the bridge. One struck the gray cover of the reactor vessel and two others hit the barge. `` We're trying to show that the local community in the gorge is not thrilled to be a nuclear highway,'' said <PERSON> Cyndi </PERSON> <PERSON> deBruler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Bingen </LOCATION>, an organizer of the demonstration. Earlier Tuesday, a fire broke out in the engine room of the tugboat pushing the barge, causing a seven-hour delay but no injuries, said <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON> of the company that owns the tug. `` At no time was there any danger of the reactor vessel going aground,'' she said. But Ms. <PERSON> DeBruler </PERSON> said the fire showed the potential for danger. `` If there were 60 mph winds, and it was powerless, it could lead to an accident,'' she said. The protesters said their main concern with the vessel is leakage into the river after it is buried.
