<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-Nature'sHand     04-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Nature's Hand,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Nature Proves Better Oil Cleanup Force Than Man</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRED BAYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP National Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 20 days of arduous work and uncounted millions of dollars, the worst effects of the nation's biggest oil spill appear to be waning Yet for all the work done by 1,000 people on the water and shoreline and other thousands of support personnel, much of the result is being attributed to the muscular forces of nature. `` The natural processes have far outweighed ours,'' <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>, the state's cleanup coordinator, said earlier this week. <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON> and other officials acknowledge much of the easing situation must be credited to nature: _ An estimated 30 to 40 percent of the 10.1 million gallons of oil that poured from the tanker <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> has been dissipated by natural evaporation of the more volatile components of the crude oil By Thursday less than 20,000 barrels, under 10 percent of the spill, will have been recovered by human effort. _ Favorable weather through most of the 20 days since the spill pushed vast amounts of the oil out of Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> and into the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> where several days of high wind and heavy seas churned and broke up the slick _ Aerial observations this week indicated that some blackened beaches on the islands and inlets of the sound are being cleansed by the heavy wave action The spill's disastrous effects are far from over. It is feared the toll of wildlife will continue and even grow as migrating birds return to the oiled beaches. It will be years before scientists know the impact on the vast ecosystem in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. Yet scientists are warning that nature must be given a big share of the cleanup work that remains. They say too much human labor and technology applied to oiled areas could do more harm than good. `` We've seen from other spills that if we hit an area too hard with things like high pressure water or heavy equipment, we wind up killing everything,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, chief of the hazardous material response branch of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said much of the shoreline hit by the oil is of a rock and gravel mix. If efforts to clean the beaches are too vigorous, he said, it could force the oil deep into the ground, where it can affect microscopic life valuable to the area's ecosystem. <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said the public's anxiety to clean the remaining mess as quickly as possible must be balanced with the realization that some areas would be better left to a slower cleanup job by nature. `` I'm optimistic that the officials here understand that,'' he said. `` I would hope that the public does n't get frustrated with what might seem like a slow process and not press us into doing it too fast.''
</TEXT>
