<FIRST>r w AM-OrphanDiseases     04-12 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Orphan Diseases,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Office Urged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressional commission on Wednesday recommended a permanent office in the federal health department to coordinate fights against so-called orphan diseases that afflict an estimated 20 million Americans. Orphan diseases are relatively rare ailments that, by definition, affect no more than 200,000 people. But because there are so many separate diseases, the total number of people suffering from them is larger than from many better-known ailments. Some diseases that qualify for orphan status are fairly well-known themselves _ such as autism, multiple schlerosis and Tay-Sachs diseases. Some, such as cholera, are common in the Third World, but rare in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Still others are obscure, such as <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>'s disease, a hereditary illness that causes liver and brain damage. The final report of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orphan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diseases </ORGANIZATION>, established by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1985, called for creation of a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orphan </ORGANIZATION> and Rare Diseases _ to be known as COORD _ within the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. It would work to: _ Increase financing for biomedical research, training, fellowships and clinical research centers _ Provide access to affordable health care for all American and eliminate health insurance restrictions on pre-existing conditions _ Speed the government approval process for medications designed to help sufferers of rare diseases _ Create a centralized information datebase on rare diseases `` Research is critical, and we must make it clear to doctors and investigators that the tratment of rare diseases is a national priority,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Jess </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thoene </PERSON>, chairman of the commission. He was joined at a news conference by Sen. <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>., and Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., main backers of the legislation that created the Both also were instrumental in passage of th Orphan Drug Act, a companion law that provides tax breaks for drug companies who make research investments to develop drugs for such a small patient base there is not a large enough market to justify the effort otherwise. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said the success of the act has been `` staggering'' and `` has accomplished mroe than <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> ever expected it to.'' <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> said more than 260 drugs have been developed for rare diseases since the Orphan Drug Act took effect, compared to less than a dozen prior to the legislation.
