<SECOND>AM-Electricity Supply,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analysts Foresee Brownouts In Northeast This Summer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> states are likely this summer to face a repeat of last year's temporary electricity shortages, and the squeeze may be a prelude to more widespread `` brownouts'' in the 1990s, energy analysts said Wednesday. `` What happens in the Northeast will be a harbinger for the rest of the country,'' said <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kujawa </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> analyst who helped direct a study on electric power trends in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Although electricity supplies for the peak use periods of summer are tightest in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, the power outlook for the nation as a whole is growing more uncertain, said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Yergin </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Cambridge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> and a partner in the study. The central problem is that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> electricity demand has grown more rapidly than expected since 1985, while utilities have chosen not to add to their generating capacity, <PERSON> Kujawa </PERSON> and <PERSON> Yergin </PERSON> told a news conference on the results of their study. The key question, they said, is who will build the generating capacity that will be needed in the 1990s. The answer is uncertain because utilities are wary of the financial risks involved in major new additions to plant capacity, while smaller power producers face an array of regulatory and other obstacles, they said. In the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION>, utilities in recent years have been forced to import power from the <LOCATION> mid-Atlantic </LOCATION>. Last summer the problem was compounded by record heat. In the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area, several thousand customers lost power for a weekend because of overheated transmission cables, and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> about 10,000 customers lost power for a day. Other parts of the country have excess generating capacity, but if demand for electricity continues growing at the pace of recent years, constraints on supply could be felt in many areas, the analysts said. Environmental and regulatory issues also may compound the problem, they said. `` What is missing is an overall framework for balancing needs for new generating capacity with environmental concerns and the questions about who will pay,'' said <PERSON> Yergin </PERSON>.
