<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Wednesday criticized Jewish demands to relocate a Carmelite convent away from the former <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> concentration camp. The Roman Catholic hierarchy has agreed to move the convent, but its failure to meet a promised Feb. 22 deadline has provoked an outcry from Jewish organizations. The newspaper <PERSON> Slowo </PERSON> <PERSON> Powszechne </PERSON> published an open letter from 1,375 people from <LOCATION> Oswiecim </LOCATION> `` protesting the pressure on the nuns to leave the building they occupy.'' <LOCATION> Oswiecim </LOCATION> is the Polish name for the city the Germans called <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>. The newspaper does not represent the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. It is owned by a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> pro-government organization called PAX. Jews want the convent moved because <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>, now a museum, holds special significance for them. About 2.8 million of the 6 million Jews killed in the Nazi holocaust died at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION>' factory-like gas chambers and crematoria and those of <LOCATION> Birkenau </LOCATION>, a larger death camp a mile away that shared the same Nazi administration Victims came from throughout <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ernst </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> <PERSON> Ehrlich </PERSON>, European Director of B'nai B'rith, said Jewish relations with the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> will `` remain frozen'' until the convent is moved. In a telephone interview from his home in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ehrlich </PERSON> cited `` resistance by the Catholic rank and file and others in all of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.'' He said he doubts Polish assurances that a start will be made soon to build a new home for the convent's 14 nuns. <PERS