<HEAD>EEC Continuing to Push Grain Exports: USDA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> continues to push grain exports aggressively, with shipments expected to be at a record level this year, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. An analysis by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> exports of wheat and coarse grains such as barley and corn are expected to total 33.3 million metric tons in 1988-89, up 39 percent from 23.9 million tons last year. International trade years begin on July 1 for wheat and Oct. 1 for coarse grains. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans, or 39.5 bushels of corn. Wheat exports by the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> are at a record 21 million tons, up from 15.3 million in 1987-88. But the coarse grains, mostly barley, also have grown and are forecast at 12.3 million tons against only 8.6 million tons last year. `` Over the past seven years, subsidized barley exports by the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> have jumped by 150 percent,'' the report said. `` While EEC barley exports comprised less than 30 percent of world barley trade as recently as the early 1980s, their share is now almost 60 percent, a growth in exports that has come at least partially at the expense of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> coarse grain market share.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the world's leading grain exporter, was forecast to have total wheat and coarse grain shipments of 103.4 million tons in the current trade year, up from 96.9 million tons in 1987-88, a 7 percent increase. Part of the growth reflects recent large corn sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and subsidized wheat sales to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is expected to import 37.5 million tons of wheat and coarse grains from all sources this year, up 2 million tons from the March forecast and 16 percent more than the 32.2 million tons imported in 1987-88. It also would be the most wheat and coarse grains imported by the Soviets since 55.4 million tons were bought in 1984-85. According to other <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> figures, the Soviets have bought about 17 million tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat and corn for delivery in the year that began Oct. 1, all but 4 million tons of it corn. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has bought about 8.5 million tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat for delivery this year, about half of the 16.5 million tons <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is expected to import from all sources in 1988-89.
