<DATELINE>WABASH, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A mysterious disease is striking infant pigs on some <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> farms and in some cases 100 percent of the infected, weakened litters have died. Eight hog operations in <LOCATION> Wabash </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> have been hit by the disease, said farmer <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Haupert </PERSON>, whose farm was stricken. `` We probably lost 30 litters,'' <PERSON> Haupert </PERSON> said. `` We're spending a couple of thousand -LRB- dollars -RRB- a week on medication.'' <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> scientists said other isolated cases have been recorded across the state. `` At this stage no one knows exactly what the disease is,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON>, professor of veterinary adult education at <LOCATION> Purdue </LOCATION>. The illness strikes sows with a loss of appetite during the latter part of their 113-day gestation period. Some farrows, or litters, are stillborn. The survivors have weakened heart membranes and cardiac muscles and a short life expectancy. In some hog operations, 100 percent of the weakened litters have died. Farmers and veterinarians first identified the disease about seven weeks ago, <PERSON> Haupert </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Purdue </ORGANIZATION> researchers are studying victims of the disease, hoping to find links to similar illnesses that damaged hog populations in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> last year. `` <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> people called it the Plague of'88,'' said <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Keffaber </PERSON>, a veterinarian with the <ORGANIZATION> Swine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Roann </PERSON>. <PERSON> Keffaber </PERSON> says infected herds in <LOCATION> Wabash </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> have 150 to 600 sows each, producing 3,000 to 12,000 piglets each year. `` It is n't killing big hogs,'' said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Runnels </PERSON>, veterinary diagnostician for swine diseases at <LOCATION> Purdue </LOCATION>. The disease is similar to other illnesses that infect swine herds, such as <PERSON> Aujesky </PERSON>'s disease, more commonly known as pseudorabies. The disease should not affect entire herds. `` It's not going to be a wipe-out disease,'' <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> said. Medication has done little to help his infected sows and piglets, <PERSON> Haupert </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> suggested that hog producers with healthy swine near infected herds should isolate their animals. Pets should not be allowed to roam near an area where the disease has been prevalent and then return to a healthy herd.
