<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Witchcraft,0660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mixture of Rites In Border Killings</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The killings linked to an alleged voodoo cult of drug smugglers appear to be part of mixture of rites with African and European elements, an anthropologist said Wednesday. Although human sacrifices were performed regularly in pre-Columbian times, `` human ritual slayings are unheard of in modern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> <PERSON> Capitaine </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Veracruz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Anthropology </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Xalapa </LOCATION>. `` Animal sacrifices are very common, however, as part of the widespread superstition and witchcraft that exists in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> nowadays,'' <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. Police in <LOCATION> Matamoros </LOCATION>, just across the border from <LOCATION> Brownsville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, have uncovered more than a dozen human bodies apparently used by drug smugglers practicing voodoo rites popularly known as santeria. The smugglers apparently tried to offer the souls of others, human and animal, to protect themselves from arrest and harm. Police had arrested several people and were looking on Wednesday for the alleged ringleader, a Cuban in his late 40s named <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Constanzo </PERSON>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials say <PERSON> Constanzo </PERSON> apparently introduced elements of santeria, a <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> Hispanic version of voodoo influenced by Roman Catholicism, to the area. Police said the victims' bodies were mutilated and that they found candles and kettles full of body parts and animal bones in the ranch. `` I'll have to have more information and maybe look for myself before I can analyze this further, but from what I saw on television last night this does n't seem to be any Mexican occult ritual,'' said <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON>, who specializes in pre-Hispanic cultures and their religious influence in modern times. `` They seem to be a Russian salad of rites from various satanic cults which the people indulged in, probably crazed by drugs,'' he said. <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> said `` lamps'' found at the ranch were actually small shot glasses blackened with soot and filled with wax, with a wick stuck in the middle. `` These are quite common in Mexican witchcraft and are typical of the European-Roman Catholic black magic rites inherited from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` But other elements like the kettles seem part of the Haitian-African rituals practiced in many places, including <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> said the African rituals were brought by slaves from <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and adapted locally to the Catholic religion. In <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> it's known as `` macumbe,'' and in the Hispanic <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>, it's called santeria `` They vary from place to place, but the main elements are almost all the same,'' <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> said. Santeria is well-known in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s Latin community, especially since 125,000 Cubans immigrated from the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Mariel </LOCATION> in 1980. Animal rights activists there have complained that practitioners torture animals and may steal and slaughter pets. Santeria priests say animal sacrifice is legal under <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law if done humanely. Priests say they kill only chickens, pigs or goats _ never cats or dogs _ and dispose of remains in a sanitary manner. <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> has dozens of santeria shops, called `` botanicas,'' that sell statues of gods, books of incantations, colored beads and scents. In Mexican marketplaces, herbs and other items are sold for witchcraft and the work of witch doctors, who are powerful figures in rural areas where Indians still live much the way they did before the Spanish came. During the Aztec Indian empire and other earlier cultures, priests sacrificed slaves or prisoners of war to the gods by cutting their hearts out or flaying or skinning them alive. `` Usually this involved a ceremony, usually a fertility rite,'' <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> said. `` In modern <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> witchcraft is very common and there are two types _ black magic, which mainly tries to cause harm to an enemy, and white magic, which seeks to do good like curing a disease,'' he said. `` And, yes ... it is common to sacrifice animals like black roosters,'' <PERSON> Winfield </PERSON> said.
