<SECOND>AM-Poland-Katyn,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Urns From Massacre Site Displayed At Army Museum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two urns holding soil from the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> graves of 4,500 Polish officers were displayed at the army museum Wednesday, indicating official <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> has come to terms with the crime widely attributed to the Soviets. A trickle of mourners, some in tears, others carrying flowers, visited the two small black containers, which Poles say have come to symbolize Soviet crimes against their country. `` It is important historically that these facts are revealed,'' said a widow who stood before the memorial with her daughter. The officers, the cream of Polish society called up from the reserves in World War II, were shot in the back of head and dumped in mass graves in <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>, near the Soviet city of <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION>. For years, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s communist government stuck by the Soviet accounting of events whereby the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> committed the murders in 1941 after invading the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. But most historians believe the Soviet secret police carried out the massacre in 1940, when the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> were still allied. And in recent months, the official Polish position has changed. In 1987, Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> agreed to appoint a joint commission to study `` blank spots'' in the two countries' histories. Polish members of the commission issued tentative conclusions, based on what officials called circumstantial evidence, pointing to Soviet responsiblity. Soviet members reportedly are still studying the case. The government press has written about <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>, a subject that had been forbidden but not forgotten by Poles. The urns were brought from <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> on April 5 by a delegation of victims' families. They were placed first at a garrison church in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> where a Mass was celebrated by army chaplains. On Wednesday, the urns were moved to the army museum, where they were placed on a pedestal bearing the words `` Soil from the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> graves'' and draped with a long banner in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s red and white colors. Overhead are hung embroidered flags from army units mustered in pre-communist <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> before World War II. Officers stand at attention on either side. In ceremonies scheduled for Tuesday, one urn will be placed on the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier and another on a monument to the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> victims at <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s Powazki cemetery. The wording on the monument, which previously blamed `` Hitlerite fascists,'' is being changed, but the government has not said what the new phrasing will be.
