<HEAD>Doctor Suspended Over `Mercy Killings' At Austrian Hospital</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 18 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Pesendorfer,
mayor. Pick up 13th pvs, `Alois Stacher...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 City authorities on Wednesday suspended the head of a hospital department where four nursing aides confessed to at least 49 `` mercy killings,'' and they ordered the exhumation of bodies of several presumed victims. Dr. <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON>'s suspension follows mounting criticism of his reported refusal to cooperate with police during an investigation last year to find evidence of mass killings at <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s Lainz hospital. Four assistant nurses arrested since Friday have confessed to killing at least 49 elderly patients with overdoses of medicine or by forcing water into their lungs. Most victims were in their 80s. Newspaper reports say the lives of 22 of the 49 victims could have been saved if <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> had cooperated last year, when senior investigator <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON> said police met `` a wall of silence'' at the hospital. <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> defended his conduct on a national television discussion Wednesday evening. <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> said he was told last April by a female doctor that another doctor, Dr. <PERSON> Waschnig </PERSON>, learned in a wine bar of rumors that patients were being `` put to rest'' by assistant nurses. <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> said he alerted doctors and senior nurses to the rumor, and ordered an immediate blood test on an 84-year-old woman who died unexpectedly days later. The blood test results prompted him to advise city medical officials and the hospital director, and police were called, <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> said. A later forensic test on the 84-year-old woman turned up nothing suspicious, officials have said. <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> said Dr. <PERSON> Waschnig </PERSON>'s name was mentioned in the presence of police, although he was not identified as the source of the rumor. A police report says <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> refused to give investigators the name of the doctor who alerted him to the possible killings. <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>'s largest daily newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> Neue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kronen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zeitung </ORGANIZATION>, asserted that if <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> and the second doctor `` had not kept quiet, it would fairly certainly have been possible to stop the series of murders a year ago.'' `` As it was, however, the sadistic nurses could kill another 22 people,'' the newspaper said. Police have not confirmed media reports that 22 people were killed in the past year. The killings reportedly began in 1983 at <LOCATION> Lainz </LOCATION> hospital's Pavilion Five, dubbed `` the Death Pavilion'' by <PERSON> Neue </PERSON> <PERSON> Kronen </PERSON> <PERSON> Zeitung </PERSON> On Wednesday, patients sat in stairwells, smoking cigarettes and whispering about <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON>'s suspension, but they refused to talk to reporters. So did Pesendorfer and hospital officials. The hospital refused to describe the function of the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> ran. However, it appears to practice general medicine on people suffering ailments related to old age. Mayor <PERSON> Helmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Zilk </PERSON> said he suspended <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> `` on the grounds of the results to date of the police investigations.'' He declined further comment. In a statement read on the television discussion program, <PERSON> Zilk </PERSON> added the suspension was intended not as a judgement of <LOCATION> Pesendorfer </LOCATION> but to facilitate further inquiries and encourage his staff to speak out. <PERSON> Alois </PERSON> <PERSON> Stacher </PERSON>, chief of the city's health department, said the suspension was linked to `` lingering lack of clarity'' over the investigation. <PERSON> Pesendorfer </PERSON> consistently has defended his role and the conduct of officials in his department at <LOCATION> Lainz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s fourth-largest hospital, since first word of the killings on Friday. Assistant nurses <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Gruber </PERSON>, 25, <PERSON> Irene </PERSON> <PERSON> Leidorf </PERSON>, 37, and <PERSON> Waltraud </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON>, 30, were detained Friday. Another assistant nurse, <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayer </PERSON>, 50, was detained Sunday after Ms. <PERSON> Ferrada-Avendano </PERSON> went to police. She too was arrested after she admitted witnessing one of the killings, <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON> said. Three other witnesses have come forward. <PERSON> Edelbacher </PERSON> said two say they witnessed killings as patients in the hospital, while another _ the daughter of a patient who has since died _ reported her mother told her about killings at the hospital. The nursing aides have not been charged, but police say Ms. <PERSON> Wagner </PERSON> alone has confessed to killing 39 patients. Her lawyer, <PERSON> Wilhelm </PERSON> <PERSON> Philipp </PERSON>, hinted it may be difficult for police to get any murder charges to stick. He was quoted by <ORGANIZATION> Austria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> as speaking of `` so-called confessions'' to police and noting state prosecutors will have to prove `` the murder really did happen'' because of his client's actions In an apparent attempt to get more evidence, city authorities late Wednesday ordered the exhumation of the bodies of several presumed victims. Officials declined to identify the bodies or say how many will be exhumed. Pesendorfer is the first doctor or official suspended because of the killings.
