<HEAD>Cholesterol Poll Finds Jump in Awareness</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of Americans who know their cholesterol level has nearly doubled in a year, and more than four in 10 say they have changed their eating habits to cut their cholesterol, a poll said Tuesday. Among 1,016 people age 18 or over polled by the <ORGANIZATION> Gallup </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> in January, 31 percent said they knew their cholesterol level. A year before, when Gallup asked the same question, just 17 percent knew. That increase `` clearly indicates that people are getting the message'' that cholesterol can contribute to heart disease, said Dr. <PERSON> DeWitt </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, the head of an advisory board on cholesterol for <ORGANIZATION> Voluntary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospitals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which commissioned the survey. The survey, conducted Jan. 9-22 and released by the organization Tuesday, found that about two-thirds of respondents said they had taken a blood test to check their cholesterol level, and four in 10 said they had changed their diet or eating habits in the past two years to reduce their cholesterol. The hospital group sponsors `` Countdown <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION>,'' at which about 450 of its member hospitals offer free cholesterol and blood pressure tests. The event this year is April 26; more than 400,000 people took the tests last year. The poll had a 3-point margin of sampling error.
