<HEAD>Soviet Scientists Claim To Duplicate U.S. Fusion Experiments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Researchers at <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> have achieved nuclear fusion at room temperature in tests similar to experiments carried out in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency said Wednesday. `` Under the guidance of Professor <PERSON> Runar </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuzmin </PERSON>, researchers at the solid matter laboratory of the physics department of <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> have confirmed the experiments of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> colleagues to obtain nuclear fusion at room temperature,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Two weeks ago, scientists at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> and at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southhampton </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> said they had achieved fusion using ordinary laboratory equipment at room temperature. Their experiments used a rod of palladium and a coil of platinum immersed in a beaker of deuterium, an isotope of hydrogen commonly found in seawater, officials at the universities said. However, many experts reamined unconvinced that fusion actually took place in those experiments, and some suggested the phenomenon may be something new to science. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> indicated similarities between the experiments at <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the campuses in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kuzmin </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> that researchers inserted electrodes _ an anode and a cathode _ into a beaker of deuterium. The electrodes were manufactured from titanium and palladium, he said. The researchers then applied electric current to the electrodes until the water reached a boiling point `` and registered the release of fast neutrons with the help of a detector,'' the news agency said. `` It is precisely judging by the release of neutrons that one can assert with confidence that the nuclear fusion reaction actually takes place,'' <PERSON> Kuzmin </PERSON> said. He said the researchers made no attempt to calculate the ratio of energy applied to the energy released. `` According to evaluations of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> scientists, this reaction probably releases four times more energy than is expended to ` stimulate' nuclear fusion,'' he said. <PERSON> Anatoly </PERSON> <PERSON> Logunov </PERSON>, a rector of <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> that a program of fundamental research into the new type of fusion will begin in the near future. At this stage, <PERSON> Logunov </PERSON> said, `` it is difficult to say whether the reaction would be economically profitable for obtaining energy on an industrial scale.''
