<HEAD>Arrests Called a Blow to Uprising, Rabbi Charged in Slaying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `In clashes...,' to UPDATE number of wounded,
army confirmation. Pick up 4th pvs, `At least...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Army officials said Wednesday the arrest of four alleged leaders of the Palestinian uprising was a major blow to the 16-month-old revolt, but Palestinians said the captures would not end their struggle. Also Wednesday, police charged a Jewish settler leader, Rabbi <PERSON> Moshe </PERSON> <PERSON> Levinger </PERSON>, with manslaughter in the death last year of an Arab shopkeeper in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> town of <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>. In clashes in the occupied <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, troops shot and wounded 15 Palestinians, including a 7-year-old boy, Arab hospital officials said. The army confirmed five casualties. At least 423 Palestinians and 18 Israelis have died in the violence, which began in December 1987. The Palestinians, whose arrests were announced Tuesday, are accused of belonging to the Unified National Leadership of the Uprising, an umbrella group of <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and Moslem fundamentalist factions. The Unified Leadership coordinates the uprising by issuing broad strategy directives through underground leaflets. Daily activities are usually planned by local popular committees. `` It's clearly a blow to the uprising. These were organizers. These were experienced leaders at the executive level,'' Col. <PERSON> Ranaan </PERSON> <PERSON> Gissin </PERSON>, an army spokesman, said of the March 5 arrests. But Palestinians said the leaders would be replaced quickly. `` It is an uprising of the people, not of a few individuals,'' said <PERSON> Radwan </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayyash </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journalists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Two of the detainees, <PERSON> Saman </PERSON> <PERSON> Khouri </PERSON>, 41, and <PERSON> Adnan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shalalda </PERSON>, 35, were remanded into custody Wednesday by a military court. <PERSON> Khouri </PERSON> allegedly belongs to the Democratic Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, a radical pro-Syrian <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> faction. The charge sheet said he was instrumental in channeling $ 1.5 million from the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> overseas to <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> factions in the occupied lands and that he helped write two underground leaflets. <PERSON> Khouri </PERSON> denied the charges. `` I did not do any of the things I'm charged with,'' he said Wednesday <PERSON> Shalalda </PERSON> was accused of being a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION>, a Marxist pro-Syrian <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> faction. He has also pleaded innocent. The two others, journalists <PERSON> Taher </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaludi </PERSON>, 35, and <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Abed </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbo </PERSON>, 28, have not been formally charged. <PERSON> Shaludi </PERSON> allegedly is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestinian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Abed </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabbo </PERSON> is accused of belonging to <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION>. `` These are the leaders of the four major terror organizations operating in the occupied territories,'' said an army official, speaking on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Levinger </PERSON>, meanwhile, was charged with manslaughter, causing bodily harm in aggravated circumstances and intentionally damaging property. The charges stem from a Sept. 30, 1988 incident in which <PERSON> Levinger </PERSON> allegedly opened fire on stone throwers in <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION> after they smashed his car windows. <PERSON> Levinger </PERSON>, 54, left the car, and fired in the air from his pistol, the charges said. He then shot and killed <PERSON> Kayed </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> Salah </PERSON>, 42, a shoe store owner who was standing outside his shop. One of <PERSON> Salah </PERSON>'s customers was also wounded, the charges said. The Jerusalem-born rabbi said he was not officially informed of the charges. <PERSON> Levinger </PERSON> is at the forefront of the Jewish settlement movement in the occupied territories. A year after <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> captured the lands in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war, <PERSON> Levinger </PERSON> founded the Jewish settlement of <LOCATION> Kiryat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arba </LOCATION> outside <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>. About 70,000 Jews live among 1.7 million Palestinians in 130 settlements in the occupied lands.
