<HEAD>Warsaw Pact Unveils Detailed Proposal On Short-Range Missile Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday unveiled a detailed proposal to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> for starting negotiations to eliminate short-range nuclear weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in a move that could widen differences within the Western alliance. The <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> already has rejected previous Soviet pressure to begin talks aimed at reducing or eliminating the tactical nuclear weapons, which have a range of less than 310 miles. But a growing number of people in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, a key <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> country, have expressed doubt the short-range weapons are still needed because of a perceived reduction of the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc threat. <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact foreign ministers, ending a two-day meeting in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, issued a communique proposing `` separate negotiations in the near future on tactical nuclear weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' The communique said `` preparations for the proposed negotiations, its mandate and who should participate can be discussed in special consultations,'' which it said the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact countries are ready to begin immediately. Most of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s short-range nuclear weapons are based in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> also said both sides should agree not to modernize their short-range nuclear weapons. The <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> has previously denounced <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s modernization plans, which also are opposed by a growing number of West Germans. `` The member states of the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> are of the opinion that a decision not to modernize tactical atomic weapons would create a favorable atmosphere for such negotiations ...'' the communique said.
