<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said Wednesday he still believes the federal government should not have taken over the Alaskan oil spill cleanup effort, although he conceded it could have gotten involved earlier. Fielding questions after a speech to a convention of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> maintained the administration moved `` more quickly and more boldly than it gets credit for.'' But at the same time, he said, `` Maybe I should accept some criticism'' that he should have moved earlier than April 7 to step up federal involvement in the environmental disaster off the coast of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that he now believes the federal government `` is properly involved'' in that effort and said `` we should not have done what some are urging upon us _ federalizing that whole cleanup.'' Last Friday, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> put <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Skinner </PERSON> in charge of coordinating actions by federal agencies in connection with cleaning up the spill from the Exxon Valdez in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>. He also ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to make military troops and equipment available to assist in the effort. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that while he was pleased the federal government has stepped up its involvement in the cleanup, `` I would also like to see more volunteers involved.'' The president said he believes liability laws should be eased to that volunteer groups wo n't be kept from helping out because of fears by the government of potentially `` outrageous liability claims.'' `` We have moved forward on the cleanup,'' he said. `` The first was containment,