<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A supersonic Concorde jet carrying 100 Americans dropped a chunk of its tail over the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday during an attempt to set a speed record, but it landed safely and passengers were reported eager to try again. The 9-foot tail section of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> plane ripped off about 25 minutes after the plane left <LOCATION> Christchurch </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, for <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> 1,000 miles away. Passengers said the plane shuddered, but the craft landed in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> about an hour later. No one was injured. The plane is attempting to set speed records for each of 12 parts of a three-week journey around the world. The passengers, who included commentator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, each paid $ 39,000 for the trip, which began in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> on April 1. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON>, an airline spokesman, said part of the rudder disintegrated while the jet was flying at 40,000 feet at about 1,500 mph _ nearly twice the speed of sound. `` It experienced a shudder while over the Tasman Sea that was thought to have been air turbulence,'' said <PERSON> Stanton </PERSON>. `` But it was a normal landing; there was no emergency.'' He said the control tower told the pilot, Capt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Leney </PERSON>, that a piece of the tail was missing. `` It was n't until we got out of the plane and saw the firetrucks and all the press ... that we knew something was wrong,'' <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON> later told <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Good Morning America.'' `` About 25 minutes after takeoff from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION> there was a large thump,'' free-lance journalist <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole-Nilva </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` Everybody looked at everybody else and lunch was served. The stewardesses looked terrified. `` The pilot came on and said there was nothing to worry about and that there was a piece loose on the airplane.'' Investigators began analyzing the Concorde's flight data recorder to find out why the tail section broke off. British Airways airport service manager <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Boody </PERSON> said the crew noticed `` unusual vibrations'' during the flight. <PERSON> Buckley </PERSON>, who helped organize the trip, planned to broadcast his television show `` Firing Line'' during stops in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>. Other stops on the itinerary include <LOCATION> Acapulco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>; and <LOCATION> Mombassa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. The trip was scheduled to end April 23 in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Lorraine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, which arranged the trip, refused to release the passengers' names. `` There were no celebrities that are household names,'' said company president <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Guiteras </PERSON>. He said all 100 passengers were `` very excited and happy with the trip,'' and that none had asked to leave the tour. Ms. <PERSON> Cole-Nilva </PERSON> said they `` ca n't wait to get back on board.'' A <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman, who by custom is not identified, said the trip would cover 38,343 miles. `` It's the first ever supersonic circumnavigation of the earth,'' she said. A prototype of the Anglo-French Concorde first flew 20 years ago. It has been in commercial service since 1976, but mainly on trans-Atlantic routes. An airline spokesman in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said a spare part was being sent, but it was not known if the plane could be repaired in time to make its scheduled flight Friday to <LOCATION> Perth </LOCATION> in western <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. The airline gave no details on how much of the tail needed to be replaced. <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> gave its Concordes a clean bill of health two months ago after inquiries that were prompted by the discovery of tiny cracks in the roof of one plane. Similar checks were made on <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Concordes </ORGANIZATION>. Concordes have been involved in a number of minor incidents, but there have been no fatal accidents.
