<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Thornburgh Repeals Meese Order</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> on Wednesday revoked a regulation promulgated by his predecessor that required the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to appoint independent counsels to investigate members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>, who had previously expressed doubt about the order issued last summer as a parting shot by outgoing Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, rescinded the regulation after President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed legislation to place lawmakers under the jurisdiction of the special prosecutor law. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s action returns to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> _ at least while <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> studies the legislation _ its traditional role in investigating allegations of criminal wrongdoing by members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been asked to review the role of the independent counsel,'' <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said in a statement. `` Until that review is completed, the previously established system for handling allegations of wrongdoing by members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which has worked well for many years, will be followed.'' The order was issued hours after <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed in his ethics package to extend to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> the law providing for court appointment of independent counsels to investigate high government officials. The law currently applies only to high-ranking executive branch officials, based on the presumption the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> would have a conflict-of-interest when called upon to investigate allegations against administration officials. Critics of the law, which included former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> officials prosecuted under it, contend it should also apply to members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>, himself the target of two independent counsel investigations that yielded no charges, promulgated the regulation requiring that the attorney general appoint special prosecutors to investigate wrongdoing by member of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON>'s order means the public integrity section will have complete jurisdiction to investigate payroll padding allegations against <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Fauntroy </PERSON>, the non-voting delegate from the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> noted that since the public integrity section of the criminal division was established in 1976, 20 members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> have been convicted of federal crimes. The department is investigating allegations that <PERSON> Fauntroy </PERSON> employed the son of Rep. <PERSON> Gus </PERSON> <PERSON> Savage </PERSON>, D-Ill., on his <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> payroll while the younger <PERSON> Savage </PERSON> was actually living in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> It would also mean that, pending any action by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal, the department would have jurisdiction to investigate any allegations of wrongdoing against <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Loye </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the public integrity section is awaiting the results of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee. It will review the panel's report to determine if a further investigation is warranted.
