<FILEID>AP-NR-04-12-89 2123EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-EthicsGlance     04-12 0493</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ethics Glance,510</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are major provisions of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposals Wednesday to tighten ethics rules for judges, members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the executive branch
</TEXT>
<NOTE>PAY RAISES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed a 25 percent pay increase for federal judges, coupled with a ban on acceptance of speaking fees and other honoraria. Associate justices of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, for example, would see their salaries rise from $ 110,000 to $ 137,000 while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> district court judges' pay would go to $ 111,900 from $ 89,500. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he supported pay hikes and a honoraria ban for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> but did not make a specific proposal.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CAMPAIGN FINANCING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed a ban on the use of leftover campaign contributions for personal use and office expenses. The law now allows anyone who held office before 1980 to use such funds for any lawful purpose. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also called for a ban on campaign contributions by political action committees, although he did not make a formal proposal on it. He also said he opposes efforts to set up a federal fund for congressional races like the taxpayer-supported one that is used for the presidential campaign.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FINANCIAL DISCLOSURE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 To tighten financial disclosure rules, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed a uniform system for the three branches of government, requiring individuals to disclose the actual value of each asset and source of income, rounded to the nearest thousand dollars. Currently, individuals are required to report only within broad categories, such as $ 5,000 to $ 15,000. More members of the executive branch also would have to file disclosure reports.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CONFLICTS OF INTEREST</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed to expand a law that forbids individuals in the executive branch from taking official actions that financially benefit them or members of their family. He said it also should apply to the judiciary and employes of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, though not to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> members themselves.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OUTSIDE ACTIVITIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Senior officials in all three branches of government would be barred from serving on the board of directors of for-profit enterprises.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>POST EMPLOYMENT ACTIVITIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed that members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> who retire or are defeated be barred for a year from contacting former colleagues to lobby them. This ban also would be extended to senior officials in the judicial branch. His proposed bill also would abolish `` compartmentalization'' of the various agencies of the executive branch for purposes of lobbying. That means that executive branch workers, currently barred for a year from lobbying their former office once they leave the government, would be under the same restriction regarding all the departments of the executive branch.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ENFORCEMENT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The independent counsel statute that has been invoked to authorize investigations of members of the executive branch would be extended to cover the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EXECUTIVE ORDER</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Under an executive order issued by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, fulltime, non-career presidential appointees in the executive branch would be prohibited from receiving any earned income from outside employment. The executive order also would give elevated rank to a designated ethics officer in each department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
