 A cold snap set low temperature records in more than 20 cities across the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> on Wednesday, and light rain and snow fell on the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> region and the northern <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Moist air steamed northward from the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and bbrought cloudy skies and scattered light showers to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. There also were scattered showers in eastern <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, and a few showers over the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> peninsula. It was sunny across most of the rest of the nation. Low pressure over <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> <PERSON> Huron </PERSON> caused the light snow and rain in the upper <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>. Grand Rapids, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, received an inch of snow during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 30 degrees at <LOCATION> Marquette </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, to 88 degrees at the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Naval </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Station </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, both in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The low for the nation Wednesday morning was 7 degrees at <LOCATION> Warroad </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>. Low temperature records that were set or tied included 32 degrees in <LOCATION> Augusta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, 37 in <LOCATION> Baton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rouge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, 29 in <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, 15 in <LOCATION> Elkins </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W.V. </LOCATION>, 41 in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, 26 in <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>,