<HEAD>Corruption Report on Car Racket Names Five Zimbabwe Ministers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN EDLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judicial commission investigating top-level corruption linked five Cabinet ministers to a black-market car racket, according to a report published Thursday. One minister quit hours earlier. The report said that of six ministers quizzed in a two-month inquiry headed by Judge <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandura </PERSON>, only Foreign Minister <PERSON> Nathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamuyarira </PERSON> was cleared of wrongdoing. Senior Cabinet Minister <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyagumbo </PERSON>, a staunch ally of President <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>, resigned his post on Wednesday, hours before the report was made public. Two of <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>'s top aides, Defense Minister <PERSON> Enos </PERSON> <PERSON> Nkala </PERSON> and Political Affairs Minister <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Shava </PERSON>, quit the government and the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Zimbabwe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Patriotic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- party after lying to the commission. But <PERSON> Sandura </PERSON>'s three-member commission said Higher Education Minister <PERSON> Dzingai </PERSON> <PERSON> Mutumbuka </PERSON> should be prosecuted, Industry and Technology Minister <PERSON> Callistus </PERSON> <PERSON> Ndlovu </PERSON> evidently lied in his testimony and doubts exist about <PERSON> Nyagumbo </PERSON>'s evidence. The commission also recommended that <LOCATION> Matabeleland </LOCATION> <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> <PERSON> Muzenda </PERSON> be prosecuted. But it exonerated army commander Gen. <PERSON> Tapfumaneyi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mujuru </PERSON>. The commission sent its report to <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> two weeks ago after interrogating 60 witnesses. It is <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>'s biggest political scandal in nine years of independence. <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> ordered the probe after a provincial newspaper exposed the racket in December. He promised the full report would be made public. While identifying abuses of power, position and privileges in the leadership, the inquiry also won <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> praise for ordering some of his closest aides to face the embarrassment of being quizzed under the public spotlight. <PERSON> Nyagumbo </PERSON>, 64, is a staunch ally of <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON>, a veteran nationalist and a founder of the government party, the nation's only legal party, in which he holds the third-highest position. <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> TV gave no explanation in announcing <PERSON> Nyagumbo </PERSON>'s resignation But aides, speaking on condition of anonymity, linked it to the corruption scandal and said <PERSON> Mugabe </PERSON> is expected to make an announcement this week about changes in government. The probe that shook <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s youngest nation was into purchases of cars and trucks from <LOCATION> Willowvale </LOCATION> car assembly plant by ministers and their friends at low, fixed prices. High-ranking officials allegedly used their influence to jump waiting lines for vehicles and then resell them illegally on the black market for up to five times what they paid. <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> has suffered a severe shortage of cars because it lacks hard currency. Would-be buyers may wait up to 10 years for a new vehicle. <PERSON> Nyagumbo </PERSON> admitted helping 38 friends buy cars, but insisted he took no money in return. The report said `` it was difficult to believe he received no benefits at all.'' The commission disputed the testimony of four other ministers who testified they bought cars but sold them at the statutory price. Charges being considered range from price control violations and sales tax evasion, which usually involve nominal fines, to perjury, which carries a maximum prison sentence of five years. The commission praised <PERSON> Geoff </PERSON> <PERSON> Nyarota </PERSON>, the crusading editor who spotlighted what became known as Willowgate.
