<FIRST>a a PM-OntheMoney Adv13   04-12 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 13,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release PMs Thursday April 13</HEAD>
<BYLINE>The Fine Points of Mortgage ``Points'' ^By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When they shop for home mortgage loans these days, most borrowers find themselves comparing not only interest rates but `` points.'' A point, simply defined, is 1 percent of the amount of a mortgage, paid by the borrower to the lender at the time a loan is made. In an era of high interest rates, banks and other financial institutions have increasingly relied on points as a way of maintaining the return they get on their lending activities without having to raise their rates to forbidding levels. For example, one <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> bank recently offered a one-year adjustable rate mortgage with no points at a starting interest rate of 10.25 percent. A competitor, meanwhile, was touting a one-year adjustable loan, with 2 -LCB- points, at 9.625 percent. Assuming you could qualify for either, which one should you choose? With adjustable mortgages in particular, there are other important variables to consider _ for example, caps on interest rate increases from year to year and over the life of the loan. But all other things being equal, the choice of a deal with or without points would depend on your circumstances as well as its mathematical merits. The higher-rate loan, for example, might appeal to people whose assets are stretched to the limit making a minimum down payment on a home, but who are confident their future earnings will cover higher monthly mortgage payments. Conversely, someone who is mainly worried about keeping monthly costs down might opt for paying points up front to get the lower rate. The burden of paying points historically has been lightened by a tax deduction. Borrowers simply included the amount of any points they paid in the mortgage-interest deduction on their tax returns. But with recent changes in the tax laws, the situation is no longer quite so simple. Points still qualify for a lump-sump deduction in the year you pay them if the charge was incurred as part of the purchase or improvement of your primary residence. Otherwise, they must be spread out for tax purposes over the life of the loan, as though they were interest payments made at periodic intervals. And to put them out in plain sight, the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s forms now require that deductions for points paid be reported on a separate line from mortgage interest. This poses a problem for people who refinance their houses. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>'s position, supported by a recent court ruling, is that points paid on refinancing do n't qualify for a lump-sum deduction, unless the money is clearly used for home improvements. The new restrictions can also trip up unwary borrowers at the time of purchase if they do n't actually pay the points in cash. `` Unfortunately,'' says <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, a tax expert at the accounting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Ernst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Whinney </ORGANIZATION>, `` many mortgage departments are not familiar enough with this rule and automatically suggest adding the points to the amount of the loan, thus killing the taxpayer's chance to qualify for current deductibility `` The solution, of course, is to pay the points from some source other than the lending bank,'' <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> observes. `` If you do not have the money available, you can borrow from another bank, so as to satisfy the test that you have paid the points from your own funds.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs April 13</NOTE>
