<FIRST>s e BC-APArts:Chaplin Adv16   04-12 1137</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Chaplin, Adv 16,1179</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>MEMORIES OF LAUGHTER</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 `` You know, this fellow is many-sided _ a tramp, a gentleman, a poet, a dreamer, a lonely fellow, always hopeful of romance and adventure. He would have you believe he is a scientist, a musician, a duke, a polo player. However, he is not above picking up cigarette butts or robbing a baby of its candy.'' _ <PERSON> Chalie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By HILLEL ITALIE</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ask <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> to say something funny and he'll come back with two words: `` <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>.'' To <PERSON> Lucille </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> was `` pure genius,'' and <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Lemmon </PERSON> calls him `` the definitive artist of this century.'' Few characters in film history ever touched as many lives as <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s Tramp. `` The Little Fellow,'' as he called him, was the epitome of the fighting underdog: down but never out; hopelessly romantic despite endless disappointment; determined to retain his dignity in the face of despair and humiliation. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> moved beyond the pie-throwing and wild chases of slapstick to make audiences understand the Tramp's feelings about himself and the world around him. He was, as the film critic <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Agee </PERSON> once said, `` the first man to give the silent language a soul.'' April 16 marks the 100th anniversary of <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s birth, and his centennial is being celebrated with tributes throughout the world. His admirers included kings and queens, soldiers and prisoners. Children chased him in the street. Writers and poets sought his company. From <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, crowds would swarm around him. Generations of performers looked to <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> as they sculpted their own brands of humor. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON> realized the extent of <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s influence after seeing his 1931 classic, `` City Lights,'' in which the Tramp befriends a millionaire and falls in love with a blind girl. `` While watching the feature, I was getting very angry at <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> because I was noticing he was doing a lot of funny things that I'd seen other comedians in other features do,'' <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON> said. `` It was only later that all those things I saw him doing were things he created, and that the other talents had copied him.'' The famous assembly-line sequence from an `` I Love Lucy'' episode in which <PERSON> Lucy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> try to keep up with the chocolates is derived from a similar scene in <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s 1936 `` Modern Times,'' in which an assembly-line worker goes crazy. The silent chase scene in <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s `` Bananas'' is another Chaplin-inspired bit. The filmmaker once said in an interview that he admired the way <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> used thin plots on which to hang funny scenes. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> could take the simplest human predicament and expand it into a lifetime. A scene in the old TV series, `` The Honeymooners,'' finds <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> locked up in <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON>'s freezing apartment on a rent strike. They're running out of food and must eat celery for dinner. Ed -LRB- Art <PERSON> Carney </PERSON> -RRB- pretends the celery is a full-course steak dinner, and eats with great flourish. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> did a similar bit when he devoured his boot in `` The Gold Rush.'' <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>, who died in 1977 following a stroke, was born in <LOCATION> Lambeth </LOCATION>, a ghetto in the south of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The son of music hall performers, his early years were difficult. His parents, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hannah </PERSON>, were separated by 1892; his father rarely made child support payments, forcing <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> and his older brother, <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, to spend time in a local orphanage. <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> was close to his mother, but she was mentally unstable and drifted in and out of nursing homes. `` I do n't think he ever lost that thing about poverty,'' recalled <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON>, a longtime friend whose book `` Remembering Charlie'' has recently been released. `` That haunts you, one day you wake up and it's all gone. That's a living nightmare. He once said to me, ` What would have happened to me if I never left <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>?''' <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> showed talent as a mime and acrobat and first appeared on stage when he was 4, singing at a nearby music hall for a wildly appreciative audience of soldiers who threw money at the young performer. By 1899, he had become one of the Eight <ORGANIZATION> Lancashire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lads </ORGANIZATION>, a traveling group of dancers and comedians. In 1908, he became a comic with the celebrated <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Karno </PERSON> company, impressing and, at times, alienating peers with his single-minded devotion to his craft. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> would later punctuate a creative dispute by insisting, `` This is my work!'' On a tour of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> late in 1912, he was spotted by a talent agent. The following year, he signed a one-year contract for $ 150 a week with <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> <PERSON> Sennett </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Keystone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Films </ORGANIZATION>, known for slapstick movies that concluded with spectacular chases. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s first motion picture, `` Making a Living,'' was released in 1914 to generally favorable reviews, although his character bore no resemblance to the Tramp. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>, wearing a top hat, monacle and droopy mustache, portrayed a slicker who tries to `` scoop'' a reporter. In his third picture, `` <PERSON> Mabel </PERSON>'s Strange Predictament,'' he unveiled the Tramp, drawing on English music hall costumes. He contrasted oversized pants and extra long shoes with a shrunken jacket and battered bowler hat, adding a tiny mustache and walking cane to give the impression of a man aspiring for status but not succeeding. `` He said the cane was the key to the whole characterization,'' <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> recalled. `` The minute he found that cane he knew he had the character. He could attack people with it, he could act like the gentleman with it.'' <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> gave the Tramp a shuffling, `` splay-footed'' walk that he picked up by imitating an old man called `` Rummy'' Banks, who used to hold horses for coachmen outside a neighborhood pub. Audiences instantly responded. A <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> reporter interviewed <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> and commented, `` You ca n't keep your eyes off his feet. Those big shoes are buttoned with 50 million eyes.'' <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> cartoons began appearing in newspapers. Songs came out _ `` Those <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> <PERSON> Feet </PERSON>,'' `` <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>, the Funniest of Them All'' and `` The Moon Shines Bright on <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>.'' By 1916, <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> was with the <ORGANIZATION> Mutual </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION>, making a staggering annual salary of $ 670,000, and critics were starting to regard his films as more than just entertainment. An article in <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>'s Weekly, `` The Art of <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>,'' praised the star in ways comedians never were. It compared the vulgarity of his films to the works of Aristophanes and <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>. In 1919, <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickford </PERSON>, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairbanks </PERSON> and <PERSON> D.W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON> formed <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> as a way of independently producing and financing their own films. `` Initially it was great,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Everson </PERSON>, a professor of cinema studies at <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. `` None of these people were getting the full results of their labor. On paper it seemed ideal, but financially it was n't feasible.''
