<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> began fleshing out his films _ mostly one-reelers _ with social commentary, relating the hardship faced by Europeans coming to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in `` The Immigrant,'' and stressing the bonds shared by warring soldiers in `` Shoulder Arms.'' His sentimental side emerged even more strongly in his feature films, starting in 1921 with `` The Kid,'' which depicted the Tramp's friendship with an abandoned boy, <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Coogan </PERSON>. The film, <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s first full-length feature, grossed $ 2 -LCB- million, made an instant star out of young <PERSON> Coogan </PERSON> and gave full display to <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s dramatic range. His next feature, `` The Gold Rush,'' came out in 1925, and is regarded by <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> and many others as his finest work. Inspired by stories of the 1898 gold rush, the movie starred <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> as the Lone Prospector, and contained one of the most famous sequences in film history, `` The Dance of the Rolls.'' <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> invites an attractive singer and her friends to dinner on New Year's Eve and enthusiastically prepares the meal. But his company never shows up and <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> falls asleep. He dreams about entertaining the guests by sticking forks in two dinner rolls and acting out a puppet-like dance on the table. In another immortal segment, he's stranded without food in a freezing cabin and boils his own boot, consuming the dinner with considerable relish, even twirling the laces like spaghetti. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> often referred to an early love affair that would forever leave him with the desire to `` reach out for beauty,'' a yearning he employed to heartbreaking effect in `` The Gold Rush'' and `` The Circus,'' in which the Tramp falls in love with a circus girl. In vain, the Tramp would pursue beautiful, unreachable women, never more movingly than in `` City Lights,'' in which he befriends a pretty blind flower girl and convinces her that he is a man of wealth and distinction. As <PERSON> Agee </PERSON> wrote, the Tramp is eventually brought down to painful reality when he raises the money necessary for the blind girl to regain her sight: `` At the end of ` City Lights,' ... -LRB- she -RRB- sees him for the first time. She has imagined and anticipated him as princely, to say the least; and it had never seriously occurred to him that he is inadequate. She recognizes who he must be by his shy, confident, shining joy as he comes silently toward her. And he recognizes himself through the terrible changes in her face. `` The camera just exchanges a few quiet close-ups of the emotions which shift and intensify in each face. It is enough to shrivel the heart to see, and it is the greatest piece of acting and the highest moment in movies.'' <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s peers praised him in similar terms. The great <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Keaton </PERSON> repeatedly deferred to his `` rival'' as being in a class by himself, writing that `` nobody ever made so many people laugh as did <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> with his Little Tramp.'' Although the onset of talking films in the late'20s ruined the careers of many stars, notably <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> was reluctant to use sound, complaining that `` dialogue, to my way of thinking, always slows action, because action must wait upon words.'' `` Motion pictures need dialogue as much as <PERSON> Beethoven </PERSON> symphonies need lyrics,'' he once said. `` City Lights'' was <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s last silent movie. In 1936, he released `` Modern Times,'' which had some crude sound effects and made a star out of <PERSON> Paulette </PERSON> <PERSON> Goddard </PERSON>, the third of his four wives. Both movies were box-office hits, as was 1940's `` The Great Dictator,'' a stinging attack against <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>, who bore an uncanny resemblance to the comic. In 1941, his artistic dreams played second to his personal life. He met and had a brief relationship with a young actress, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>. She later accused <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> of fathering her child. Although blood tests backed up his claims that the baby was n't his, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> jury said he was, causing considerable damage to his reputation and paving the way for right-wing branding of communism. With McCarthyism in full and furious throttle, <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>, an outspoken liberal and supporter of the wartime alliance with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, came under harsh attack. He had lived in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> but had never become a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizen, considering himself `` a citizen of the world.'' When he went to <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> in the early'50s to film `` Limelight,'' his entry permit was revoked. The man who had embodied the American Dream, working his way from music hall performer to international celebrity, lived his final years in <LOCATION> Vevey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. `` I never saw him depressed,'' <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> said. `` He loved <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. He would say, ` After all, that's where I met <PERSON> Oona </PERSON>.''' <PERSON> Oona </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, daughter of the playwright <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>, was 18 when they married. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> was 54. `` She devoted her whole life to him,'' <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> said. `` She knew how to handle an artist. <PERSON> Oona </PERSON> is completely reserved, self-effacing; never wanted the career, never wanted the limelight. She was in love with him her whole life. `` She always said, ` When I was young he looked after me, now that he's an old man, it's my turn to look after him.''' Their eight children carved their own fame: <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON>, the oldest, became an actress who soared to fame in <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lean </PERSON>'s 1965 epic, `` Dr. Zhivago.'' <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON> portrayed <PERSON> Hemingway </PERSON>'s wife in a TV miniseries about the writer. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> played one of the leads in `` King in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'' when he was 9. All three children had walk-ons in `` Limelight.'' <PERSON> Victoria </PERSON> runs a French circus called <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cirque </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Imaginaire </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> is a businessman. <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> lives in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Ilya </PERSON> <PERSON> Salkind </PERSON>, producer of the Superman movies. <PERSON> Annette </PERSON> recently appeared in a stage production of <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Shepard </PERSON>'s `` Buried Child'' in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON>, 25, the youngest, appeared in `` Notes From the Underground'' in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> also had two children from his second wife, <PERSON> Lita </PERSON> <PERSON> Grey </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> won a Tony playing opposite <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Holliday </PERSON> in `` Bells Are Ringing,'' and co-starred with Barbra Streisand in `` Funny Girl'' on <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> died about 20 years ago. After `` <PERSON> Monsieur </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdoux </PERSON>'' flopped in 1947, <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> never again regained his commercial appeal. `` Limelight,'' released in 1952, contained a memorable musical sequence with <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Keaton </PERSON>, but had only moderate success. He made just two more movies, both poorly received: `` A King in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' and `` A Countess From <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>,'' a 1967 comedy starring <PERSON> Marlon </PERSON> <PERSON> Brando </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sophia </PERSON> <PERSON> Loren </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> spent the last 10 years of his life collecting honors, composing new scores for his movies and working on a project, `` The Freak.'' It was never completed. He returned briefly to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1972 to receive an `` honorary'' Oscar from the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sciences. The <ORGANIZATION> Cannes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> had paid tribute to him the year before, and the <ORGANIZATION> Venice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Festival </ORGANIZATION> gave him a special Golden Lion award. He received knighthood from Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> in March 1975. A fan of the underdog to the end, <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> expressed admiration for <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallone </PERSON>'s `` Rocky,'' murmuring, `` excellent, excellent,'' as he watched the movie. `` He just took life as it came,'' <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON> said. `` He never spoke about death. He never spoke about old age. He felt he was still young. He never lost his sense of curiosity.''
