<HEAD>MEMORIES OF LAUGHTER</HEAD>
<HEAD>A White Marble Tombstone Has Replaced the Wooden Cross</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 CORSIER-SUR-VEVEY, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ The plain wooden cross that marked the burial site before the sensational theft of the body, was replaced long ago. Now there's a white, marble tombstone with the simple inscription: `` <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>, 1889-1977,'' dropping the `` Sir'' to which the world-famous comedian was entitled after being knighted by Queen <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> in 1975. Under a bright spring sun, the forget-me-nots and the white and rose hyacinths seemed freshly planted. Other graves in the Swiss cemetery were equally well kept, bearing names more familiar in the village where the reclusive actor never really struck roots. `` I am sure their gardner will prepare some special floral decoration for the anniversary,'' said <PERSON> Etienne </PERSON> <PERSON> Buenzod </PERSON>, a communal employee who takes care of the cemetery of <LOCATION> Corsier </LOCATION>, a wine-growing village overlooking <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> where <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> spent the last 25 years of his life. `` I saw some of his films but I saw him in person only once during these 25 years. He was a very discreet man.'' So seems his widow, <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Oona </PERSON>, who still resides in the <ORGANIZATION> Chaplins </ORGANIZATION>' Manoir de Ban _ an 18th-century manor just above <LOCATION> Corsier </LOCATION> _ but who is rarely seen in the village. <PERSON> Corsier </PERSON> was preparing for weeks of festivities marking the 100th anniversary of <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON>'s birth. He was the village's most famous resident and, posthumously, put its name on front pages worldwide when two would-be extortionists snatched his body. Buenzod discovered the theft on March 2, 1978, more than two months after <PERSON> Chaplin </PERSON> died on Christmas Day following a stroke. The 300-pound oak-and-silver coffin with the body inside was recovered 10 weeks later, buried in a cornfield about 10 miles from here. News of the bizarre theft spread throughout the world. The Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> TASS </ORGANIZATION> denounced it as `` typical for the atmopshere of crime in the inhuman Western world.'' But a Swiss court took a more lenient view of the two perpetrators, political refugees from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. `` I wanted to get money without harming anyone,'' testified <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Wardas </PERSON>, the theft's bungling Polish mastermind, who was arrested when he ran out of coins at a public phone during ransom negotiations with the <ORGANIZATION> Chaplins </ORGANIZATION>' family lawyer. The two also had to dig up the coffin for a second time because they had forgotten to take photographs to prove they were holding it. <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Oona </PERSON>, according to the lawyer, categorically rejected ransom demands, lowered gradually from $ 600,000 to $ 100,000, saying her husband was `` in heaven and in my heart.'' <PERSON> Wardas </PERSON> was sentenced to 4 -LCB- years in prison, but freed after three years because of good conduct.
