<FIRST>s a BC-ArmenianOdysseyIII Adv16   04-12 0955</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Armenian Odyssey III, Adv 16,0988</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Here for Surgery, an Armenian Boy's Ways Become American</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP NewsPhoto Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos scheduled to move April 13</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kocharian </PERSON>, a dark-haired, doe-eyed boy who suffered a crushed hand when last December's earthquake in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> collapsed his school, has spent the last two months in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, undergoing reconstructive surgery. As he awaits two more operations to give him operable fingers, he absorbs <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> culture. This is the third report in an intermittent series tracking <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>'s progress. The story is by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> reporter <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Rule </PERSON>, with LaserPhotos by Photographer <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sancetta </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE RULE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kocharian </PERSON> arrived here two months ago for treatment of injuries suffered in December's Armenian earthquake, he was a 9-year-od in a gray suit who talked about soccer and chess. Now it's blue jeans and sneakers, video games and Pee Wee <PERSON> Herman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>, now 10, is one of 37 Armenian children to be treated at 10 American hospitals under a program sponsored by Project Hope. Four of the children, including <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>, are being treated at Children's Hospital of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> lost his right eye and the fingers on his right hand when his grade school collapsed in the Dec. 7 quake, which left thousands of his countrymen dead, injured or homeless. Soviet doctors gave him a glass eye before he left for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Although overwhelmed with curiosity when he first arrived, he waited to ask questions until he was alone with <PERSON> Annadid </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohanian </PERSON>, whose family is host to <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> and <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON>. And he kept his bandaged, maimed hand in his suit pocket. Finally, fascination with that most American of love objects, the automobile, pulled <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> out of his shell. Within days of arriving in February, he had seen Camaros, Porsches and Cadillacs. With a toy camera from the Ohanians, he shot two rolls of film, photographing the <PERSON> Ohanian </PERSON> family cars, a Corvette, two Fieros and a <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>, from every angle. `` When we go back,'' he told his father firmly, `` I do n't want to ride in our afto mekana,'' a nondescript Russian-made car. `` I will build my own car,'' he said, planning to work as an auto mechanic like his father. His father, <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON>, also has changed. At first quiet and reserved, he is quicker to chat with American-Armenians who visit. `` How do you do?'' he says in English to other visitors. <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON>, a stocky, 34-year-old with specks of gray in his hair, also has become more vocal about what he sees as shortcomings in the Soviet system. When the Ohanians first brought <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON> to their small variety store in west <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, he was amazed at the number of available items. `` He asked, ` Why ca n't we have this back home?''' <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohanian </PERSON> said. Recently, a <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reporter called from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON> answered questions with questions, smiling and winking at the other Armenians present. `` Who is going to pay for all this?'' he was asked. `` Do n't you know?'' he replied, adding, `` Not your country. Project Hope will. And my countrymen will.'' Later, <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON> said he was angry because the Soviets have placed severe restrictions on what he and <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> can bring back to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Project Hope has been giving the children's guardians $ 10 a day toward living expenses. <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON> has spent most of the money on <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>; he has bought himself only a white jogging suit. Now, he said, he is afraid he will not be able to bring back any of the clothes or toys <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> has received as presents since arriving here. <PERSON> Ohanian </PERSON> said the Soviets have an official list of what may be brought into the country. It specifies only one of each item: one pair of pants, one shirt, one toy and so on. <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON> has not yet told <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>, who continues to play with the Matchbox cars and other toys he's received from well-wishers in places from <LOCATION> Northborough </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Tustin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>. Last month, two of <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>'s toes were transplanted to his right hand so he would have fingers The operation was not wholly successful and circulation problems developed, so doctors sewed <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>'s new fingers into a skin flap on his stomach to help with the healing. The doctors say <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> needs two more operations to build the toes into complete fingers. Naturally right-handed, the boy takes therapy to strengthen his left-handed abilities. He plays magnetized pick-up sticks, bounces basketballs and writes letters for his physical therapist, <PERSON> Dore </PERSON> <PERSON> DiBerardino </PERSON>. Most days are spent at the Ohanians' store. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> answers the telephone with a bright greeting, `` Armenian Touch.'' For lunch everyday, he orders his favorite American sandwich _ corned beef on rye, hold the cheese. When he talks, English words pop into his conversation. At the Ohanians' suburban <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chester </LOCATION> home, <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> steers a riding mower around the backyard with his left hand, wrenching the wheel back and forth. Recently, he and his father were watching an Armenian-language video, `` Baghdassar Akhbar.'' <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> laughed occasionally at the family comedy, but his eyes brightened when <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON> switched to `` Pee Wee <PERSON> Herman </PERSON>'s Big Adventure'' on cable television. <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> laughed at every visual gag, hugging his stomach. When Pee Wee's motorcycle hit a billboard, the boy screamed in English, `` Oh, my god,'' and fell back laughing. For himself, <PERSON> Sarkis </PERSON> admits to enjoying <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallone </PERSON>'s `` Rambo'' and `` Rocky'' movies `` They are much different now,'' said <PERSON> Ohanian </PERSON>, an Armenian immigrant who is housing the Kocharians because he wanted to help `` the children who are Armenian's future.'' `` They have come here to get medical treatment,'' he said, tousling <PERSON> Karen </PERSON>'s hair. `` But we're sending them back American rebels.''
</TEXT>
