<HEAD>Judge Drops One Count, Refuses to Move Bilzerian Securities Trial
to Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has dismissed one of 12 felony counts against <ORGANIZATION> Singer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> chairman and corporate takeover specialist <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> but refused to shift the securities fraud trial to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>, 38, is accused of violating securities and tax laws, conspiracy and making false statements in connection with four failed takeover transactions in 1985 and 1986. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> on Tuesday dismissed one count of making false disclosure statements in a transaction with <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. One felony count remains connected to that deal The defense had asked <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> to dismiss all charges against <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>, who has denied the government's claims. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> also denied a request to move the trial to federal court in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> lives. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said he expects the trial, scheduled to begin May 1, to last four to six weeks. The government contends <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> made millions of dollars by accumulating stock in takeover targets _ specifically, <ORGANIZATION> Hammermill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, H.H. <ORGANIZATION> Robertson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Cluett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ concealing ownership of the stocks in secret accounts and then selling his holdings after the stock price had risen. None of the charges involve <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON>'s $ 1.06 billion takeover of Singer, a defense contractor he acquired last year after a lengthy struggle. Much of the government's case is derived from information supplied to the government by <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> broker <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON>, who has admitted to two felonies for violating federal securities laws. <PERSON> Jefferies </PERSON> also supplied information for the government's stock manipulation case against <ORGANIZATION> GAF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which ended in a second mistrial last month. <PERSON> Bilzerian </PERSON> faces a maximum penalty of five years in jail and a $ 250,000 fine on each count.
