<HEAD>Butcher Trustee Awarded $19.3 Million In Damages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has ordered C.H. Butcher Jr. and others to pay $ 19.3 million in damages for a plot to hide the bankrupt financier's wealth when his banking empire collapsed. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> awarded the damages Tuesday to bankruptcy trustee <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> to pay creditors in the last major civil lawsuit against Butcher. A federal jury in <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION> last month found that C.H. Butcher Sr. and two disbarred <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> lawyers conspired to help the younger Butcher keep some of his wealth. The jury found the senior Butcher, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwind </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> guilty under the Racketeering Influenced Corrupt Organizations Act following a four-day trial. C.H. <PERSON> Butcher </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and his brother, 1978 <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Democratic gubernatorial candidate <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Butcher </PERSON>, were convicted in connection with the 1983 failure of their twin banking empires, <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> chain. Testimony included assertions that <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> received $ 1.6 million from Butcher Jr. to buy gold bars and coins after the financier had declared bankruptcy. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> has been trying to locate the $ 1.6 million and documents produced at the trial showed that <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> was the last person known to have handled it. <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> was not present at the trial. He and <PERSON> Schwind </PERSON>, his former law partner, were disbarred after their money-laundering convictions in an unrelated case. The jury awarded damages of $ 245,437 from Butcher Sr., $ 474,288 from <PERSON> Schwind </PERSON> and $ 1.63 million from <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>. Under a RICO provision tripling that amount, the total jury award was $ 7,049,176. But <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> found that <PERSON> Schwind </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> were liable for $ 4,889,999 after the damages were tripled, while Butcher Jr. was responsible for $ 11,276,250 individually and $ 2,422,583 with his wife, <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON>. The suit initially sought $ 126 million in damages from a dozen defendants. But after a series of out-of-court settlements, it changed the damages sought to $ 8 million from five defendants.
