<SECOND>PM-Time-Warner, Bjt,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Exec Says Company Will Be Active In Cable, Defends Merger Plans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> intends to become a major player in basic cable television programming, says the media giant's chairman, who also took a few jabs at broadcasters who have tried to belittle the medium In a speech Tuesday to cable executives and advertisers, Chairman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> also defended Time's planned $ 15 billion merger with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> against criticism from those he called the `` lords of leverage'' and domestic rivals that he said were suffering `` merger envy.'' The deal is subject to review by federal regulators and approval by the shareholders of both companies. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> recently announced it will not oppose the merger. Time is only indirectly involved in basic cable programming _ those channels cable subscribers automatically receive _ through investments in companies such as <ORGANIZATION> Turner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which operates the <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> and other basic cable services. <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Box </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary owns two premium cable TV services, <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Cinemax </ORGANIZATION>, for which cable subscribers pay an additional fee over their monthly charge. There have been published reports that <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> is considering launching a comedy cable network. While <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> did not specifically address those reports in his talk to the <ORGANIZATION> Cabletelevsion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>'s annual conference, he said, `` Our goal in basic -LRB- cable -RRB- is to develop a high-quality, well-defined, differentiated service with the audience appeal of <ORGANIZATION> HBO </ORGANIZATION> and the channel identification of <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION>.'' He noted that some critics have described the basic cable audience as `` underpaid, overaged, out of touch.'' But <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said cable has changed television from a passive medium with three main viewing choices into a responsive medium `` able to appeal to a far broader range of tastes and interests than before.'' He said some broadcasting executives have responded by refusing to acknowledge the changes that have occurred in viewing habits. Time recognizes the networks' dilemma, <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said, because it faced the same situation in magazines in the late 1970s, when regional and specialized magazines began attracting bigger increases in ad spending than Time's mass market magazines were seeing. <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> said Time faced up to market realities and built itself into the nation's largest regional publisher. `` I do n't want to sound like I'm making a blanket attack on broadcast. I'm not,'' he said. He said there are a lot of `` smart people at the networks'' who know the value and potential of cable and are trying to get in on it. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, for instance, launches a business network on basic cable next week. Regarding the merger plan with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> repeated the dealmakers' assertions that the pact would guarantee an American company will be among the few global giants expected to dominate the communications business by the mid-1990s. He said some of Time's and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic competitors do n't like the deal <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> called it a `` chronic case of merger envy.'' `` My advice to them is to save their energy to invest in finding the kind of match that will help keep them competitive in global markets,'' he said. <PERSON> Munro </PERSON> also chided `` the lords of leverage,'' who he said `` hate the deal because it builds a new company instead of breaking up two existing ones.'' `` To put it politely, I think their expressed concern that shareholders are being shortchanged by this deal resembles nothing so much as the cat worrying about the good health of the canary,'' he said.
