<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CLARIFY that IMF money would help reduce
payments on debt to spur growth that would reduce debt. Pick up 2nd pvs,
`Significantly, the...'. Also moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has signed an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> under which <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will receive up to $ 3.65 billion over three years to help reduce payments on its $ 107 billion debt, the treasury secretary announced Tuesday. The goal is to reduce the net outflow of funds to provide the investment money needed to spur growth and reduce the debt. Significantly, the accord stipulates that the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> supports <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s current economic austerity and modernization programs and requires no additional austerity measures, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said. That means that the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> will not require any further devaluations of the <LOCATION> Mexican </LOCATION> peso, as has been called for in previous agreements in an effort to stimulate exports, an official said on condition of anonymity. `` The agreement reached with the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> constitutes a plain endorsement of the economic strategy of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said. `` The fund has completely subscribed to this strategy.'' The treasury chief also announced <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will conclude `` in the next several days'' an agreement with the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> for $ 1.5 billion in credits to support the government's restructuring programs. <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> agreement will promote <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s efforts to reach restructuring agreements with creditor government banks. Tuesday's accord may be extended for a fourth year at <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s request On April 19, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will formally present to creditor banks its proposals to reduce the foreign debt's value, cut servicing and obtain additional lending over several years, <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said. The loan amount is $ 2.79 billion in Special Drawing Rights, a denomination used by the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> and also known as `` paper gold.'' SDRs are a measure of a nation's reserve assets in the international monetary system, and their value is based on an amalgam of major currencies. The value in this case is $ 1.30 for every dollar in the reserve assets, making the total loan worth about $ 3.6 billion. Mexican President <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gortari </PERSON>, who took office Dec. 1, has pressed efforts to cut the outflow of capital needed to revitalize <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s stagnant economy. Economic growth was nil last year. <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> has sought to reduce foreign debt servicing, which will cost about $ 16 billion this year, and to obtain $ 7 billion through lower payments and new loans each year for the next six years.
