<HEAD>Wendy's Offers Money-Back Guarantee In Taste Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEITH ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is putting its money where its mouth is by offering customers a refund if they do n't think they've tasted the best hamburger in the business. The promise is part of a six-week advertising campaign in which <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s, one of the nation's largest fast-food chains, proclaims itself the winner in a taste contest with industry leader <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The ad campaign started Monday and ends in mid-May. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rath </PERSON>, executive vice president of marketing, said the suburban Dublin-based company favors the taste-test over a campaign emphasizing discounts. `` The problem I have with discounts is that if you lower the price, then it must have only been worth that much in the first place,'' <PERSON> Rath </PERSON> said in an interview Tuesday. `` We've got a product that we have a lot of confidence in its worth and its value to the consumer. Nobody's done this before.'' The money-back guarantee is in addition to the company's policy of refunding money to dissatisfied customers. Under the special offer, the company will refund the price of the hamburger to customers who do not agree that the one they just ate was the best in the burger business. <PERSON> Rath </PERSON> said the company did not estimate how much the special refunds would cost the company. `` We do n't think we're going to lose any more than we would on a legitimate complaint of a product that does n't meet our standards,'' he said. Industry analyst <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> New-York </ORGANIZATION> based marketing research company <ORGANIZATION> Malcolm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Knapp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> called the promotion `` a great proposition.'' He said <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s came out No. 1 in a taste test this year in Restaurant and Institutions magazine. <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> said the strategy will cost the company less money than such promotions as couponing or discounts. `` Couponing always gives away products, for sure. And if you do discounting, you're giving away money,'' he said. <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> also said the campaign will bring more people into <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s restaurants <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s is virtually tied for third with <ORGANIZATION> Hardee </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in size among national fast-food chains. Burger King, a division of <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is second. <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s spokesman <PERSON> Denny </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> said the refund strategy was tested in eight markets last year. `` It was never a problem,'' he said. He said customers trying to abuse the offer likely will be discovered because patrons tend to return to the same restaurant. He also said only a few people would try to get refunds by going to several restaurants. `` Is it worth it to do that for $ 1.39? I do n't think so,'' <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> said. The advertising campaign includes a claim of taste superiority over <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s contends customers surveyed at random in 1987 and 1988 preferred <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s hamburgers by a 2-1 ratio over those offered by <ORGANIZATION> McDonald </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Rath </PERSON> said the company hired <PERSON> C.J </PERSON>. Research of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> to conduct the surveys. About 1,500 consumers were interviewed quarterly. McDonald's spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Onoda </PERSON> was not available for comment Tuesday and did not return a call seeking comment. <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON>'s, with about 3,750 restaurants nationwide, has annual sales of nearly $ 3 billion. It earned $ 28.5 million last year, continuing to rebound from 1986, when it lost $ 4.9 million. The company made $ 4.5 million in 1987.
