<SECOND>PM-Corporate Tax,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Introduced To SImplify Corporate Tax</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, has introduced a bill to simplify the corporate minimum tax Committee aides said no estimate of how the bill would affect tax collections has been produced, nor is it clear which industries, if any, would be hurt by the change. In a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON> said Tuesday he is open to suggestons for changes in the bill. However, he added, `` I will oppose any attempt to extend the arbitrary book-income preference beyond its scheduled expiration at the end of this year.'' The corporate minimum tax is designed to ensure that any firm with a profit pays some tax, no matter how many deductions are claimed. A company calculates is liability under the regular corporate tax, figures the minimum tax and pays the larger figure. The 1986 tax overhaul amended the minimum levy to base the tax in 1987 through 1989 on the concept of book income, a term normally used in reporting profits to stockholders but not to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>. For years starting in 1990, the law drops the book-income concept and substitutes one known as `` adjusted current earnings.'' <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>'s bill would eliminate adusted current earnings as a separate tax preference. Instead, individual items of earnings would be treated as separate preferences, eliminating one complicated set of calculations.
</TEXT>
