<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar edged higher against major foreign currencies in light European trading early today. Gold prices were lower. Dealers said they expected the dollar to trade within a narrow range, squeezed by dollar demand and fears of intervention by central banks, before Friday's release of several key <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic indicators, including wholesale prices and the trade deficit for February. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the dollar rose 0.23 Japanese yen to a closing 132.85 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it eased to 132.80 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday's prices, included: 1.8850 West German marks, up from 1.8825; 1.6651 Swiss francs, up from 1.6582; 6.3638 French francs, up from 6.3535; 2.1268 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1225; 1,380.50 Italian lire, up from 1,379.25; and 1.1900 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1888 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.6910 from $ 1.6995 late Tuesday. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 383.80 a troy ounce, down from $ 385.25 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 384.15 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 384.20, down from $ 385 bid late Tuesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.29 to close at a bid $ 385.08. Silver bullion was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 5.82 a troy ounce, down from $ 5.84 bid late Tuesday.
