<HEAD>Davis, Northwest Exchange Lawsuits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARBARA DEWEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has asked a federal judge to prevent <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> billionaire <PERSON> Marvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> from meddling with its unions while <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who is seeking to buy the nation's fourth-largest airline, filed a separate lawsuit seeking to invalidate the company's `` poison pill'' takeover defense <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who has offered to buy <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s parent, <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, for $ 2.62 billion or $ 90 a share, said the airline's litigation is without merit and infringes on workers' rights to `` to satisfy themselves as to the plans and intentions of a new owner.'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, an oilman with interests in real estate and entertainment, also said he planned a shareholder proxy fight to win control of the airline's board at the company's May 15 shareholders meeting. No hearing date was immediately set on <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' suit, filed Tuesday in <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> is based <LOCATION> Eagan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION> and incorporated in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. Meanwhile, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> MacLauglin </PERSON> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION> set a hearing for Thursday to consider <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s request for an injunction against <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> to prevent him from negotiating with the carrier's pilots and other union workers. Northwest's suit, also filed Tuesday, contended <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and his partnership were illegally interfering with the companies' relations with <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> labor unions The suit claimed <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> is trying to block completion of a collective bargaining agreement being negotiated between <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> and its 5,000-member pilots' union. The suit said <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> contacted the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> on April 4, the day after he announced his takeover bid in a letter to the board of directors of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> also has talked to the leader of the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lodge </ORGANIZATION> 143, which recently agreed to recommend adoption of a proposed new contract for 10,500 clerical workers at <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, the lawsuit said. In addition, <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> had talked with the leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union, which represents <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s 6,500 flight attendents. The Northwest suit says <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the partnership he controls, `` are seeking to have the unions negotiate with them, to usurp <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s contractual and statutory role and thereby to interfere with and disrupt <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>'s prospective and existing contractual and labor relations with its principal unions.'' Last Friday, <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors rejected <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' offer, calling it inadequate. The board also reaffirmed its intention to maintain the nation's fourth-largest airline as an independent entity. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday the airline would not comment on <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>' suit `` at least until we study the complaint.'' <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, meanwhile, called the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> action `` entirely without merit.'' Northwest's board approved the poison pill March 27, saying it wanted to make the company less attractive to a hostile suitor intending to break up the company. The plan would take effect when a person or group acquires 15 percent of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s common stock or announces a tender offer that would result in ownership of 15 percent or more of the voting power of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> stock. The plan would allow the company to double the number of existing shares and offer them to shareholders other than the acquirer at half the market price, said <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbons </PERSON>. The effect would be to require a hostile bidder to buy twice as many shares to gain control of the company, making the bid twice as expensive. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> complained in his suit that the plan would improperly interfere with the solicitation of proxies he expected to conduct in advance of the May 15 shareholders meeting. He is seeking an order to temporarily restrain <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION> from distributing special stock-buying rights to shareholders under the pill. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> owns 3 percent of <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>'s stock. Shortly before he made his offer, <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> announced that a separate group of investors was interested in buying <ORGANIZATION> NWA </ORGANIZATION>. The identity of that group, which owns 4.9 percent of the stock, has not been disclosed.
