<HEAD>Minimum Wage Debate Continues, Amendment Process Moving Slowly</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs with unrelated amendment tacked on to minimum
wage bill; pickup graf 4 pvs, Polls have.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> today added to legislation to increase the minimum wage an unrelated amendment increasing by roughly $ 1,000 the amount of outside income Social Security recipients are allowed to earn before facing benefit cutbacks. The amendment, passed 86-11, was one of more than a dozen up for consideration today before a final vote on the minimum-wage bill, which calls for raising the hourly base wage from its current $ 3.35 to $ 4.55 by October 1991. The slow pace of the debate on amendments threatened to push the final vote back until Thursday. Passage of the amendment offered by Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, R-Colo., also brought the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> bill far out of line with a House-passed bill, meaning that after final <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passage a conference committee would be needed to draft a compromise The current outside earnings limit is $ 8,880 for Social Security recipients 65 years of age or older. After crossing that limit recipients lose $ 1 of benefits for every $ 2 in earned income. The amendment would increase the limit for most of those affected to $ 9,960. It would apply to Social Security recipients between the ages of 65 and 70. The earnings limit expires after age 70. Most of the senators who spoke against the amendment said they supported its goal but questioned the appropriateness of adding it to the minimum-wage bill. They also said that benefits to thousands of Social Security recipients likely would have to be cut to pay for the proposal. The amendment is not related to the mininum wage but <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rules do not prohibit tacking on other proposals to legislation being considered by the full body. An impasse between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and the Democratic congressional leadership that threatens prospects for a higher minimum wage has both sides trying to convince the public the other side is to blame. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he will veto the Democratic plan, a development that could lead to a ninth consecutive year without an increase in the minimum wage despite the first White House support this decade for some boost. Polls have shown the public overwhelmingly supports an increase, a fact not lost during the partisan wrangling. `` This legislation will be a test of whether we indeed are seeking a kinder, gentler nation,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said Tuesday, criticizing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for refusing to budge from his proposal, which would raise the minimum wage from $ 3.35 an hour to $ 4.25 an hour by January 1992. <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s `` kinder, gentler'' campaign rhetoric is at odds with his opposition to the Democratic bill, particularly when the president is backing expanded tax breaks for capital gains enjoyed largely by the nation's wealthy. `` How can anyone justify wanting to give $ 30,000-a-year tax cuts to the richest Americans and at the same time oppose 30 cents an hour more for the poorest Americans?'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>. `` That's not right. It's wrong. It's unfair.'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> spoke just before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> rejected <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal, 58-41, largely along party lines, and instead amended a bill by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., to bring it more in line with the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill That revision was approved, 61-39. The administration fired back quickly, with <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> raising the prospect that the partisan squabbling would result in no increase in the minimum wage this year. `` Democrats have no one to blame but themselves,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said. `` The Democrats decided they'd rather fight than win. Unfortunately, the people who really lose are the ones who can least afford it.'' In addition to favoring a smaller increase in the general minimum wage, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has insisted on letting employers pay new workers a sub-minimum `` training wage.'' Democrats, who long opposed a sub-minimum, agreed this year to include one in their proposal in hopes of making it more acceptable to the administration. The Kennedy bill, as amended, contains a provision allowing employers to pay new workers a sub-minimum wage for up to 60 days; <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has insisted on a six-month training wage. Republicans, however, are confident a veto can be upheld and are in no mood for a compromise on the overall dispute. `` There is n't going to be a compromise,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Republican leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>. `` It's going to be $ 4.25 an hour and a six-month training wage, period.''
</TEXT>
