<HEAD>Famous Munich Beer Maker May Restart Direct Exports of Renowned Brew</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Loewenbraeu company of <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>, one of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s best-known beer-makers with origins that date to the 14th century, is considering direct exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> after watching falling sales of its licensed brew in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. But Loewenbraeu general manager and director <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiedemann </PERSON> emphasizes direct export is just one option under consideration, and praises the cooperation with licensing partner <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>. `` We have an excellent business and personal relationship with <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Wiedemann </PERSON> emphasized in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. But he said that in an effort to raise flagging sales, `` among the various options that we have, there could also possibly be the resumption of direct exports.'' He confirmed published reports that annual sales of the licensed Loewenbraeu on the American market, which began under a pact made in the early 1970s, has dropped by nearly a third since then. <PERSON> Fritz </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Loewenbraeu </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said the licensed product is brewed in Miller-run <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> breweries. Direct exports means Loewenbraeu would ship its beer made in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The remarks by <PERSON> Wiedemann </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kuhn </PERSON> appeared to surprise officials at <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION>, a leading American brewer, which has a contract with Loewenbraeu that runs through 1992. `` Quite frankly, I'm really puzzled by what they said,'' said <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Jurkowski </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Miller </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman reached by telephone. `` The very nature of that contract would prevent some of those other options from taking place.'' She said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and Loewenbraeu officials conferred in February, a meeting she said the West German company found highly encouraging. The Lowenbraeu general manager suggested that in the future, both companies might collaborate on direct exports of Loewenbraeu to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He declined to be more specific. Loewenbraeu already has formed a company in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Loewenbraeu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, to study the possibility of direct exports and to look into other possibilities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Wiedemann </PERSON> said. `` Because our sales in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> are down, we must undertake decisive strategy changes,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Loewenbraeu </ORGANIZATION> executive said. He acknowledged that the higher price for export beer is one consideration weighed by officials of the 606-year-old brewery. The general manager noted <ORGANIZATION> Loewenbraeu </ORGANIZATION> is considering the purchase of a brewing facility on <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s northern coast, near seaports and much closer to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> than the current facilities deep in southern <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION>. `` That way we do n't just have <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as a possible market, we also have a substantial export business in the whole world,'' <PERSON> Wiedemann </PERSON> said. He added: `` The beer we would brew there, if in fact we buy a brewery, would be made according to the same recipe as we have here in <LOCATION> Munich </LOCATION>.'' The northern facility also could figure into Loewenbraeu's plans to become a dominant brand within this country of 61.3 million people. `` Among the approximately 1,150 breweries now in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, there is none with a market share of more than 5 percent. There are so many suppliers, and there is no truly national brand,'' he said. End adv for weekend editions April 15-16
