<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most grain and soybean futures prices closed higher Wednesday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid rumors of new Soviet buying interest in the wheat market. But oat futures retreated, reflecting the abundance of foreign oats available on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. Crop futures were buoyed early in the session by an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report indicating the nation's grain stockpiles were declining more rapidly than most analysts had believed. Rumors surfaced at midday that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was eyeing new purchases of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat, which would be a significant development because the Soviets have already purchased all the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat earmarked for sale to them this year at subsidized prices. The moderate decline in oat futures was overdue, said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Homan </PERSON>, an independent oat trader in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` We've needed to divorce ourselves from the strength of the other grain markets,'' he said. `` There's a scarcity of American oats but an abundance of foreign oats.'' At the close, wheat was 2 -LCB- cents to 7 -LCB- cents higher with the contract for delivery in May at $ 4.03 -LCB- a bushel; corn was 2 \ cents to 3 -LCB- cents higher with May at $ 2.67 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 1 -RCB- cents to 4 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 1.79 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 6 -LCB- cents higher with May at $ 7.27 a bushel
