<HEAD>J.P. Morgan Announces Drop In Quarterly Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's fourth largest bank holding company, on Wednesday reported a 36 percent drop in its first quarter profit over a year ago. The company said it netted $ 180 million, or 96 cents a share, for the three months ended March 30, compared with earnings of $ 280 million, or $ 1.52 per share, in the 1988 period. The first quarter of 1988 included a gain of $ 43 million related to a federal tax refund. Chairman <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> attributed the decline largely to the rise in worldwide interest rates over the past year, which he said limited opportunities in areas such currency and securities trading. Most effected was net interest income, which tumbled to $ 299 million in the first quarter from $ 438 million a year ago. Total non-interest income also declined, to $ 394 million from $ 435 million, while non-interest expenses eased to $ 436 million from $ 511 million. <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> allowed less for credit losses during first quarter, $ 10 million against $ 50 million a year ago. It said total allowances from such losses, including loans to Third World countries, was $ 1.49 billion, during the quarter, down from $ 1.57 billion.
