<HEAD>Palladium Cracks $170, A 5{-Year High, On Fusion Reports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Palladium futures prices surged to their highest level in nearly 5 -LCB- years Wednesday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> amid optimism that recent nuclear fusion experiments could spur demand for the metal as an ingredient in the power plants of tomorrow. Other precious-metal futures prices also advanced. On other markets, cocoa futures plunged; gasoline prices rose but other energy futures were mixed; grains and soybeans were mostly higher; and livestock and meat futures were mixed. Palladium settled $ 4.40 to $ 5.15 higher with the contract for delivery in June at $ 173.65 a troy ounce. The move marked palladium's first foray above $ 170 since December 1983, when the metal reached nearly $ 180 a troy ounce. Palladium prices have risen in 10 of the 13 trading sessions since March 23, when two chemists announced they had achieved nuclear fusion at room temperature using palladium as a catalyst in an experiment at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION>. Fusion is the joining together of hydrogen atoms to produce enormous amounts of energy. It is the process that powers the sun and stars, and scientists seeking a cheap energy source have long sought to harness it. Last week, palladium for June delivery went as high as $ 169 an ounce only to collapse on Friday amid skepticism about the <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> findings. But on Monday, researchers at <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> A & amp; M and <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tech </ORGANIZATION> announced they had replicated at least part of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> results, bringing new buyers into the usually quiet palladium market. Some of the buying interest in palladium spilled over into the platinum market Wednesday. `` The rally in palladium created a psychological environment which was conducive to rallies in the other precious metals,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Anagnos </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Thomson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> McKinnon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. But analysts said the moderate rise in gold and silver futures was more likely a response to inflation jitters and signs that the dollar's recent strength has peaked. Platinum settled $ 3.30 to $ 3.80 higher on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> with May at $ 531.80 a troy ounce. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold settled $ 2.20 to $ 2.40 higher with June at $ 392.10 a troy ounce; silver was 3.2 cents to 4.2 cents higher with May at $ 5.895 a troy ounce. Cocoa futures plummeted on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Coffee, <ORGANIZATION> Sugar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Cocoa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on rumors that the <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, the world's largest cocoa producer, had sold an unknown quantity of cocoa through the Swiss trade house Intercafco, which denied any such deal. Cocoa settled $ 30 to $ 56 lower with May at $ 1,272 per metric ton. Unleaded gasoline futures rose sharply for the fourth straight day on supply concerns. The crude - and heating-oil market were quiet West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled unchanged to 6 cents higher with May at $ 20.64 a barrel; heating oil was unchanged to 5 cents lower with May at 53.20 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .20 cent lower to 1.11 cents higher with May at 70.11 cents a gallon. Most grain and soybean futures prices rose on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid rumors of new Soviet buying interest in the wheat market. But oat futures retreated, reflecting the abundance of foreign oats available on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. Wheat settled 2 cents to 6 -RCB- cents higher with May at $ 4.03 a bushel; corn was 2 \ cents to 3 -LCB- cents higher with May at $ 2.67 -RCB- a bushel; oats were 1 -RCB- cents to 4 -LCB- cents lower with May at $ 1.79 a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents to 7 cents higher with May at $ 7.27 -LCB- a bushel On the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, weak cash markets and profit-taking weighed on the cattle futures while pork futures advanced on ideas that farmers soon will be busy with spring planting and will be marketing fewer hogs. Live cattle settled .87 cent lower to .60 cent higher with April at 76.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .12 cent to .93 cent lower with April at 76.40 cents a pound; live hogs were .12 cent to .38 cent higher with April at 39.95 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .20 cent lower to .28 cent higher with May at 33.30 cents a pound.
