<HEAD>IMF Loan Could Bolster Mexico's Standing In Talks With Commercial
Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s latest $ 3.65 billion loan from the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> will likely improve its standing in upcoming debt restructuring talks with commercial bank creditors, bank executives said Wednesday. Negotiations between the country and a 13-member bank committee are set to begin April 19 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. At that time, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will formally propose a reduction in the value of its foreign debt, a cut in servicing and additional lending over several years, according to <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON>. He said <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> will offer banks the option of exchanging old debt for Mexican bonds that discount debt principal and reduce interest rates. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, struggling to overcome the burden of payments to commercial banks and governments on its $ 107 billion foreign debt, is the developing world's second-largest debtor behind <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, which owes $ 121 billion. The three-year agreement reached with the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday is the first from the international lending community since <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> outlined a debt-reduction plan last month that he hoped would help ease payment terms on the developing world's $ 1.32 trillion foreign debt. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rhodes </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Citicorp </ORGANIZATION> vice president, said the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> pact `` is a positive signal as it forms an important part of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s economic program. `` It will help facilitate negotiations with the bank advisory group'' next week, he said in a statement. The $ 3.65 billion <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> loan will be used to bolster the country's foreign exchange reserves and spur economic development <PERSON> Aspe </PERSON> said the agreement `` is a fundamental change from the past,'' since the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION> recognizes <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s need to set its growth priorities first and schedule debt servicing accordingly. Many bankers agreed that the pact amounted to an endorsement of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s economic policies, which included tough inflation-fighting programs. `` <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is a country that has made significant progress. It deserves whatever kind of special treatment might be meted out,'' said <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkinson </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Montreal </ORGANIZATION> and an advisor to the bank creditors committee.
