<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced Wednesday that it settled allegations that <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> discriminated against foreign-born job applicants. The issue was raised by the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigrants </ORGANIZATION>' Rights, which brought the charges on behalf of a job applicant who wished to remain anonymous, said <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Siskind </PERSON> of the department's Office of Special Counsel. The center alleged that <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> was requiring that foreign-born applicants for bank tellers show `` green cards,'' known formally as alien registration cards, even though they already had provided adequate documentation to satisfy the requirements of the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986. That act, among other things, required employers to ensure that they did not hire illegal aliens, and threatened them with fines if they failed to do so. `` In the case of <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION>, it was discriminating against foreign-born employees by forcing them to produce documents that it was n't forcing its other employees to produce,'' <PERSON> Siskind </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> deems drivers licenses, school identity cards with photographs, voter registration cards and draft cards, among other documents, as sufficient to establish identity. Although the allegation against <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> focused on just one individual, <PERSON> Siskind </PERSON> said, `` We did learn that they had been doing it as a policy. They had instructed their personnel people to do that, but as soon as we began our investigation and informed them of the law, they agreed to stop the policy.'' The investigation began Jan. 27 and was settled Monday, he said. In the settlement, <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> agreed to accept any and all documents allowed by the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> to satisfy the requirement that the person is eligible for employment and agreed to treat all applicants and employees the same. It will not pay any fine to the government or any back pay to the affected individual, who was subsequently hired, <PERSON> Siskind </PERSON> said.
