<HEAD>Hewlett-Packard To Buy Apollo In Move To Seize Workstation Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Hewlett-Packard will ...,' to CORRECT amount
of HP's offer to $13.12 per share sted $13.25.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANTHONY MARQUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALO ALTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> moved to seize leadership in the $ 4 billion computer workstation market Wednesday, announcing an agreement to buy <ORGANIZATION> Apollo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 476 million in cash. <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION>'s surprise announcement stole some thunder from rival <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which had chosen Wednesday to announce what it called the most significant new products in its history. Apollo and <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> together would have 30.4 percent of the burgeoning workstation market, capturing the lead from Sun, which has 28.3 percent, according to <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a San Jose-based research firm. The workstation market is expected to grow at a 30 percent clip through 1993, according to <PERSON> Alea </PERSON> <PERSON> Fairchild </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION>. Workstations are single-user computers that resemble personal computers but are usually quicker, bigger and with larger screens and better graphics. They were originally used mostly by scientists and engineers but are being increasingly targeted to everyday personal and business use. `` It signals a real major commitment on our part to the workstation portion of our business,'' said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Watts </PERSON>, director of marketing in <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION>'s computer products sector. <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> will offer $ 13.12 per share for Apollo's estimated 36 million shares of common stock outstanding and will begin its tender offer within five business days Apollo shot up $ 4.62 -LCB- to $ 12.75, a gain of more than 50 percent in heavy over-the-counter trading of 10 million shares. <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> fell 75 cents to $ 53.50 in consolidated <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> trading. The deal requires regulatory approval and the tender of at least 51 percent of Apollo stock by shareholders. Apollo, a Fortune 500 company founded in 1980 and based in <LOCATION> Chelmsford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, was the pioneer of computer workstations, but has suffered setbacks in the race with <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> and lost money in two consecutive quarters last year. It squeezed out a profit of $ 2.1 million for the year as a whole on sales of $ 654 million. Apollo will likely operate as a division within <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION>'s workstation group once the acquisition is completed, which should be in 90 days, said <PERSON> Watts </PERSON>. Apollo Chairman and CEO <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanderslice </PERSON> termed the transaction a `` win-win'' situation for both companies. He said he did not foresee major layoffs resulting from the purchase. <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> said it will benefit from Apollo's strength in computer networking and its large customer base and motivated workforce. <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> will bring its strength in the graphics area to Apollo, which could use the help, as well as financial resources that includes $ 9.8 billion in revenues last year. `` The Hewlett-Apollo thing was pretty astonishing,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, a senior analyst and editor of San Francisco-based <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Letter </ORGANIZATION>. `` What Hewlett I think is doing here is building a lot of customer relationships that they are then going to migrate over into the Unix world.'' Workstations run on Unix, an operating system that excels in communications and the ability to carry out multiple tasks simultaneously. The announcement came as <ORGANIZATION> Sun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Microsystems </ORGANIZATION> rolled out a line of Sparcstation computers that boast sophisticated new graphics and digital sound, plus higher speeds and a circuit board that allows full-motion video on a computer screen. It also launched a family of Sun-3 workstations. `` I think that maybe is purely coincidental but it is interesting timing,'' said <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosak </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` I think it buys <PERSON> Hewlett </PERSON> more visibility in an interesting market. They certainly have the money to do it and Apollo did need financial help,'' said <PERSON> Bosak </PERSON>, who called the $ 476 million a fair price. <ORGANIZATION> Hewlett-Packard </ORGANIZATION> had 16.9 percent of the 1987-88 market share and Apollo had 13.5 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Dataquest </ORGANIZATION> said.
